{"title_page": "Ren\u00e9 Vidal", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Rene Vidal\n| image = Rene Vidal.png\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1974}}\n| birth_place = [[Lautaro, Chile]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| residence = [[Fulton, Maryland]]\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = Chilean\n| fields = [[Machine learning]]<br>[[Computer vision]]<br/>[[Medical Image Computing]]<br>[[Robotics]]<br>[[Control theory]]\n| workplaces = [[The Johns Hopkins University]]\n| alma_mater = [[Universidad Catolica de Chile]]<br>[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title = Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA): An Algebraic Geometric Approach to Subspace Clustering and Motion Segmentation\n| thesis_url = http://vision.jhu.edu/assets/VidalPHD03.pdf\n| thesis_year = 2003\n| doctoral_advisor = [[S. Shankar Sastry]]<ref name=\"advisor\">{{MathGenealogy|id=70150}}</ref>\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| awards = [[AIMBE Fellow]] (2020) <br> [[IAPR Fellow]] (2016) <br> [[IEEE Fellow]] (2014) <br> [[IAPR Aggarwal Prize]] (2012) <br> [[Sloan Fellow]] (2009) <br> [[Office of Naval Research|ONR]] Young Investigator Award (2009) <br> [[National Science Foundation|NSF]] CAREER Award (2004)\n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.cis.jhu.edu/~rvidal/}}\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9 Vidal''' (born 1974) is a [[Chile]]an [[electrical engineering|electrical engineer]] and [[computer science|computer scientist]] who is known for his research in\n[[machine learning]],<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Elhamifar | first1 = E. | last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = Sparse subspace clustering: Algorithm, theory, and applications | doi = 10.1109/TPAMI.2013.57 | pmid = 24051734 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence | volume = 35 | issue = 11 | pages = 2765\u20132781 | year = 2013| arxiv = 1203.1005 }}</ref> [[computer vision]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Tron | first1 = R. | last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = A Benchmark for the Comparison of 3-D Motion Segmentation Algorithms | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2007.382974 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2007}}</ref>\n[[medical image computing]],<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Zappella | first1 = L. | last2 = Bejar | first2 = B. | last3 = Hager | first3 = G. | last4 = Vidal | first4 = R. | title = Surgical gesture classification from video and kinematic data | doi = 10.1016/j.media.2013.04.007 | pmid = 23706754 | journal = Medical Image Analysis | volume = 17 | issue = 7 | pages = 732\u2013745 | year = 2013}}</ref> [[robotics]],<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Shakernia | first2 = O. | last3 = Kim | first3 = H.J. | last4 = Shim | first4 = D.H. | last5 = Sastry | first5 = S.S. | title = Probabilistic pursuit-evasion games: theory, implementation, and experimental evaluation | doi = 10.1109/TRA.2002.804040 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 662\u2013669 | year = 2002}}</ref> and [[control theory]].<ref name=\"Vidal:CDC03\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Soatto | first2 = S. | last3 = Ma | first3 = Y. | last4 = Sastry | first4 = S.S. | title = An algebraic geometric approach to the identification of a class of linear hybrid systems | doi = 10.1109/CDC.2003.1272554 | conference = IEEE Conference on Decision and Control | year = 2003}}</ref> He is the Herschel L. Seder Professor of the [[Johns Hopkins Department of Biomedical Engineering]], and the founding director of the Mathematical Institute for Data Science (MINDS).\n\n== Biography ==\nVidal did his undergraduate studies at the [[Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile]] where he received his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in 1995 and his [[Master of Engineering]] degree in 1996. After one year at DICTUC he enrolled at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], where he was awarded an [[M.Sc.]] and a [[Ph.D.]] in [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Computer Science]] in 2000 and 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Rene|last=Vidal |title=Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA): An Algebraic Geometric Approach to Subspace Clustering and Motion Segmentation | publisher=The University of California, Berkeley|date=2003 |url=http://vision.jhu.edu/assets/VidalPHD03.pdf}}</ref> Before joining [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 2004, he was a Research Scientist at the [[Australian National University]] and [[NICTA]]. Vidal is currently a [[Professor]] in the Department of Biomedical Engineering of [[Johns Hopkins University]] with secondary appointments in [[Applied Mathematics and Statistics]], [[Computer Science]], [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]], and [[Mechanical Engineering]]. He is also a faculty member in the Center for Imaging Science, the Institute for Computational Medicine and the Laboratory for Computational Sensing and Robotics. In 2017, Vidal became the founding director of the Mathematical Institute for Data Science (MINDS).\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nIn 2004, Vidal was recognized with the [[National Science Foundation CAREER Awards]].<ref name=CAREER>{{cite web |title=NSF CAREER Award|url=https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0447739}}</ref>\nIn 2009, Vidal was recognized by the [[Office of Naval Research]] with an award from the Young Investigator Program.<ref name=ONR-YIP>{{cite web |title=ONR YIP| url=https://www.onr.navy.mil/Media-Center/Press-Releases/2009/Young-Investigator-Award-Recipients.aspx}}</ref>\nIn 2009, Vidal was recognized with a [[Sloan Research Fellowship]]<ref name=Sloan>{{cite web |title=Sloan Research Fellowship|url=https://sloan.org/past-fellows}}</ref> in [[computer science]] by the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation]].\nIn 2012, Vidal was recognized by the [[International Association for Pattern Recognition]] by winning the J.K. Aggarwal Prize<ref name=Aggarwal>{{cite web |title=J.K. Aggarwal Prize|url=http://www.iapr.org/fellowsandawards/awards_aggarwal.php}}</ref> for outstanding contributions to generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) and subspace clustering in computer vision and pattern recognition.\nIn 2014, Vidal was elected [[IEEE Fellow]]<ref name=IEEE>{{cite web |title=IEEE Fellow|url=https://www.ieee.org/2014Fellowclass}}</ref> for contributions to subspace clustering and motion segmentation in computer vision.\nIn 2016, Vidal was elected IAPR fellow<ref name=IAPR>{{cite web |title=IAPR Fellow|url=http://www.iapr.org/news/index.php?id=743}}</ref> for contributions to computer vision and pattern recognition.\nIn 2020, Vidal was inducted into AIMBE College of Fellows<ref name=AIMBE>{{cite web |title=AIMBE Fellow|url=https://aimbe.org/dr-rene-vidal-inducted-into-aimbe-college-of-fellows/}}</ref> for outstanding contributions to medical image analysis and medical robotics.\n\n\n== Work ==\n\nVidal has been a prominent scientist in the fields of [[machine learning]],<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\"/> [[computer vision]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\"/> [[medical image computing]],<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\"/> [[robotics]]<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\"/> and [[control theory]]<ref name=\"Vidal:CDC03\"/> since the 2000s. In [[machine learning]], Vidal has made many contributions to subspace clustering,<ref name=\"Vidal:SPM11\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | title = Subspace Clustering | doi = 10.1109/MSP.2010.939739 | journal = IEEE Signal Processing Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | pages = 52\u201368 | year = 2011| bibcode = 2011ISPM...28...52V}}</ref> including his work on Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA),<ref name=\"Vidal:PAMI05\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Ma | first2 = Y. | last3 = Sastry | first3 = S.S. | title = Generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) | doi = 10.1109/TPAMI.2005.244 | pmid = 16355661 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 1945\u20131959 | year = 2005| arxiv = 1202.4002 }}</ref> Sparse Subspace Clustering (SSC)<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\"/> and Low Rank Subspace Clustering (LRSC).<ref name=\"Vidal:PRL14\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Favaro | first2 = P. | title = Low Rank Subspace Clustering (LRSC)| doi = 10.1016/j.patrec.2013.08.006 | journal = Pattern Recognition Letters | volume = 43 | pages = 47\u201361| year = 2014}}</ref> Much of his work in [[machine learning]] is summarized in his book Generalized Principal Component Analysis.<ref name=\"Vidal:Springer16\">{{Cite book | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Ma | first2 = Y. | last3 = Sastry | first3 = S.S. | title = Generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) | doi = 10.1007/978-0-387-87811-9 | publisher = Springer Verlag | volume = 40 | year = 2016| series = Interdisciplinary Applied Mathematics | isbn = 978-0-387-87810-2 }}</ref> Currently, he is working on understanding the mathematical foundations of [[deep learning]], specifically conditions for global optimality.<ref name=\"Haeffele:CVPR17\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Haeffele | first1 = B.| last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = Global optimality in neural network training | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2017}}</ref> In [[computer vision]], Vidal has made many contributions to [[rigid motion segmentation]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\"/><ref name=\"Vidal:CVPR04\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Hartley | first2 = R.| title = Motion segmentation with missing data using PowerFactorization and GPCA | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2004.1315180 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2004}}</ref> [[activity recognition]]<ref name=\"Chaudhry:CVPR09\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Chaudhry | first1 = R. | last2 = Ravichandran | first2 = A.| last3 = Hager | first3 = G. | last4 = Vidal | first4 = R. | title = Histograms of oriented optical flow and Binet-Cauchy kernels on nonlinear dynamical systems for the recognition of human actions | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2009.5206821 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2009}}</ref> and dynamic textures.<ref name=\"Ravichandran:CVPR09\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Ravichandran | first1 = A. | last2 = Chaudhry | first2 = R. | last3 = Vidal | first3 = R. | title = View-invariant dynamic texture recognition using a bag of dynamical systems | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2009.5206847 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2009}}</ref> In [[medical image computing]], Vidal developed algorithms for recognition of surgical gestures.<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\"/> In [[robotics]], Vidal developed algorithms for distributed control of unmanned vehicles.<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\"/> In [[control theory]], Vidal studied algebraic conditions for [[observability]] of [[hybrid system]]s <ref name=\"Vidal:CDC02\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Chiuso | first2 = A.| last3 = Soatto | first3 = S. | title = Observability and identifiability of jump linear systems | doi = 10.1109/CDC.2002.1184923 | conference = IEEE Conference on Decision and Control | year = 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Vidal:HSCC03\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Chiuso | first2 = A.| last3 = Soatto | first3 = S. | last4 = Sastry | first4 = S.S. | title = Observability of Linear Hybrid Systems | doi = 10.1007/3-540-36580-X_38| conference = International Workshop on Hybrid Systems: Computation and Control | year = 2003}}</ref> as well as algebraic geometric approaches for the identification of [[hybrid system]]s.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vidal, Rene}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:American electronics engineers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Rene Vidal\n| image = Rene Vidal.png\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1974}}\n| birth_place = [[Lautaro, Chile]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| residence = [[Fulton, Maryland]]\n| citizenship = \n| nationality = Chilean\n| fields = [[Machine learning]]<br>[[Computer vision]]<br/>[[Medical Image Computing]]<br>[[Robotics]]<br>[[Control theory]]\n| workplaces = [[The Johns Hopkins University]]\n| alma_mater = [[Universidad Catolica de Chile]]<br>[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title = Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA): An Algebraic Geometric Approach to Subspace Clustering and Motion Segmentation\n| thesis_url = http://vision.jhu.edu/assets/VidalPHD03.pdf\n| thesis_year = 2003\n| doctoral_advisor = [[S. Shankar Sastry]]<ref name=\"advisor\">{{MathGenealogy|id=70150}}</ref>\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = \n| awards = [[AIMBE Fellow]] (2020) <br> [[IAPR Fellow]] (2016) <br> [[IEEE Fellow]] (2014) <br> [[IAPR Aggarwal Prize]] (2012) <br> [[Sloan Fellow]] (2009) <br> [[Office of Naval Research|ONR]] Young Investigator Award (2009) <br> [[National Science Foundation|NSF]] CAREER Award (2004)\n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.cis.jhu.edu/~rvidal/}}\n}}\n'''Ren\u00e9 Vidal''' (born 1974) is a [[Chile]]an [[electrical engineering|electrical engineer]] and [[computer science|computer scientist]] who is known for his research in\n[[machine learning]],<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Elhamifar | first1 = E. | last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = Sparse subspace clustering: Algorithm, theory, and applications | doi = 10.1109/TPAMI.2013.57 | pmid = 24051734 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence | volume = 35 | issue = 11 | pages = 2765\u20132781 | year = 2013| arxiv = 1203.1005 }}</ref> [[computer vision]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Tron | first1 = R. | last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = A Benchmark for the Comparison of 3-D Motion Segmentation Algorithms | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2007.382974 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2007}}</ref>\n[[medical image computing]],<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Zappella | first1 = L. | last2 = Bejar | first2 = B. | last3 = Hager | first3 = G. | last4 = Vidal | first4 = R. | title = Surgical gesture classification from video and kinematic data | doi = 10.1016/j.media.2013.04.007 | pmid = 23706754 | journal = Medical Image Analysis | volume = 17 | issue = 7 | pages = 732\u2013745 | year = 2013}}</ref> [[robotics]],<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Shakernia | first2 = O. | last3 = Kim | first3 = H.J. | last4 = Shim | first4 = D.H. | last5 = Sastry | first5 = S.S. | title = Probabilistic pursuit-evasion games: theory, implementation, and experimental evaluation | doi = 10.1109/TRA.2002.804040 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Robotics and Automation | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 662\u2013669 | year = 2002}}</ref> and [[control theory]].<ref name=\"Vidal:CDC03\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Soatto | first2 = S. | last3 = Ma | first3 = Y. | last4 = Sastry | first4 = S.S. | title = An algebraic geometric approach to the identification of a class of linear hybrid systems | doi = 10.1109/CDC.2003.1272554 | conference = IEEE Conference on Decision and Control | year = 2003}}</ref> He is the Herschel L. Seder Professor of the [[Johns Hopkins Department of Biomedical Engineering]], and the founding director of the Mathematical Institute for Data Science (MINDS).\n\n== Biography ==\nVidal did his undergraduate studies at the [[Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile]] where he received his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in 1995 and his [[Master of Engineering]] degree in 1996. After one year at DICTUC he enrolled at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], where he was awarded an [[M.Sc.]] and a [[Ph.D.]] in [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Computer Science]] in 2000 and 2003, respectively.<ref>{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Rene|last=Vidal |title=Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA): An Algebraic Geometric Approach to Subspace Clustering and Motion Segmentation | publisher=The University of California, Berkeley|date=2003 |url=http://vision.jhu.edu/assets/VidalPHD03.pdf}}</ref> Before joining [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 2004, he was a Research Scientist at the [[Australian National University]] and [[NICTA]]. Vidal is currently a [[Professor]] in the Department of Biomedical Engineering of [[Johns Hopkins University]] with secondary appointments in [[Applied Mathematics and Statistics]], [[Computer Science]], [[Electrical and Computer Engineering]], and [[Mechanical Engineering]]. He is also a faculty member in the Center for Imaging Science, the Institute for Computational Medicine and the Laboratory for Computational Sensing and Robotics. In 2017, Vidal became the founding director of the Mathematical Institute for Data Science (MINDS).\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nIn 2004, Vidal was recognized with the [[National Science Foundation CAREER Awards]].<ref name=CAREER>{{cite web |title=NSF CAREER Award|url=https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0447739}}</ref>\nIn 2009, Vidal was recognized by the [[Office of Naval Research]] with an award from the Young Investigator Program.<ref name=ONR-YIP>{{cite web |title=ONR YIP| url=https://www.onr.navy.mil/Media-Center/Press-Releases/2009/Young-Investigator-Award-Recipients.aspx}}</ref>\nIn 2009, Vidal was recognized with a [[Sloan Research Fellowship]]<ref name=Sloan>{{cite web |title=Sloan Research Fellowship|url=https://sloan.org/past-fellows}}</ref> in [[computer science]] by the [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation]].\nIn 2012, Vidal was recognized by the [[International Association for Pattern Recognition]] by winning the J.K. Aggarwal Prize<ref name=Aggarwal>{{cite web |title=J.K. Aggarwal Prize|url=http://www.iapr.org/fellowsandawards/awards_aggarwal.php}}</ref> for outstanding contributions to generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) and subspace clustering in computer vision and pattern recognition.\nIn 2014, Vidal was elected [[IEEE Fellow]]<ref name=IEEE>{{cite web |title=IEEE Fellow|url=https://www.ieee.org/2014Fellowclass}}</ref> for contributions to subspace clustering and motion segmentation in computer vision.\nIn 2016, Vidal was elected IAPR fellow<ref name=IAPR>{{cite web |title=IAPR Fellow|url=http://www.iapr.org/news/index.php?id=743}}</ref> for contributions to computer vision and pattern recognition.\nIn 2020, Vidal was inducted into AIMBE College of Fellows <ref name=IAPR>{{cite web |title=AIMBE Fellow|url=https://aimbe.org/dr-rene-vidal-inducted-into-aimbe-college-of-fellows/}}</ref> for outstanding contributions to medical image analysis and medical robotics.\n\n\n== Work ==\n\nVidal has been a prominent scientist in the fields of [[machine learning]],<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\"/> [[computer vision]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\"/> [[medical image computing]],<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\"/> [[robotics]]<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\"/> and [[control theory]]<ref name=\"Vidal:CDC03\"/> since the 2000s. In [[machine learning]], Vidal has made many contributions to subspace clustering,<ref name=\"Vidal:SPM11\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | title = Subspace Clustering | doi = 10.1109/MSP.2010.939739 | journal = IEEE Signal Processing Magazine | volume = 28 | issue = 2 | pages = 52\u201368 | year = 2011| bibcode = 2011ISPM...28...52V }}</ref> including his work on Generalized Principal Component Analysis (GPCA),<ref name=\"Vidal:PAMI05\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Ma | first2 = Y. | last3 = Sastry | first3 = S.S. | title = Generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) | doi = 10.1109/TPAMI.2005.244 | pmid = 16355661 | journal = IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence | volume = 27 | issue = 12 | pages = 1945\u20131959 | year = 2005| arxiv = 1202.4002 }}</ref> Sparse Subspace Clustering (SSC)<ref name=\"Elhamifar:TPAMI13\"/> and Low Rank Subspace Clustering (LRSC).<ref name=\"Vidal:PRL14\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Favaro | first2 = P. | title = Low Rank Subspace Clustering (LRSC)| doi = 10.1016/j.patrec.2013.08.006 | journal = Pattern Recognition Letters | volume = 43 | pages = 47\u201361| year = 2014}}</ref> Much of his work in [[machine learning]] is summarized in his book Generalized Principal Component Analysis.<ref name=\"Vidal:Springer16\">{{Cite book | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Ma | first2 = Y. | last3 = Sastry | first3 = S.S. | title = Generalized principal component analysis (GPCA) | doi = 10.1007/978-0-387-87811-9 | publisher = Springer Verlag | volume = 40 | year = 2016| series = Interdisciplinary Applied Mathematics | isbn = 978-0-387-87810-2 }}</ref> Currently, he is working on understanding the mathematical foundations of [[deep learning]], specifically conditions for global optimality.<ref name=\"Haeffele:CVPR17\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Haeffele | first1 = B.| last2 = Vidal | first2 = R. | title = Global optimality in neural network training | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2017}}</ref> In [[computer vision]], Vidal has made many contributions to [[rigid motion segmentation]],<ref name=\"Tron:CVPR07\"/><ref name=\"Vidal:CVPR04\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Hartley | first2 = R.| title = Motion segmentation with missing data using PowerFactorization and GPCA | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2004.1315180 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2004}}</ref> [[activity recognition]]<ref name=\"Chaudhry:CVPR09\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Chaudhry | first1 = R. | last2 = Ravichandran | first2 = A.| last3 = Hager | first3 = G. | last4 = Vidal | first4 = R. | title = Histograms of oriented optical flow and Binet-Cauchy kernels on nonlinear dynamical systems for the recognition of human actions | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2009.5206821 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2009}}</ref> and dynamic textures.<ref name=\"Ravichandran:CVPR09\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Ravichandran | first1 = A. | last2 = Chaudhry | first2 = R. | last3 = Vidal | first3 = R. | title = View-invariant dynamic texture recognition using a bag of dynamical systems | doi = 10.1109/CVPR.2009.5206847 | conference = IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition |year = 2009}}</ref> In [[medical image computing]], Vidal developed algorithms for recognition of surgical gestures.<ref name=\"Zappella:MedIA13\"/> In [[robotics]], Vidal developed algorithms for distributed control of unmanned vehicles.<ref name=\"Vidal:TRA02\"/> In [[control theory]], Vidal studied algebraic conditions for [[observability]] of [[hybrid system]]s <ref name=\"Vidal:CDC02\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Chiuso | first2 = A.| last3 = Soatto | first3 = S. | title = Observability and identifiability of jump linear systems | doi = 10.1109/CDC.2002.1184923 | conference = IEEE Conference on Decision and Control | year = 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Vidal:HSCC03\">{{Cite conference | last1 = Vidal | first1 = R. | last2 = Chiuso | first2 = A.| last3 = Soatto | first3 = S. | last4 = Sastry | first4 = S.S. | title = Observability of Linear Hybrid Systems | doi = 10.1007/3-540-36580-X_38| conference = International Workshop on Hybrid Systems: Computation and Control | year = 2003}}</ref> as well as algebraic geometric approaches for the identification of [[hybrid system]]s.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vidal, Rene}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Catholic University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:Computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:American electronics engineers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Vidal"}
{"title_page": "Facebook Platform", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = January 2019}}\n{{Short description|Application platform around Facebook's social network}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2019}}\n\nThe '''Facebook Platform''' is the set of services, tools, and products provided by the [[social networking service]] [[Facebook]] for [[third-party software component|third-party]] developers to create their own [[application software|applications]] and services that access data in Facebook.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nThe current Facebook Platform was launched in <time>2010</time>.<ref name=\"F8\">{{cite news | url=https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/564/ | title=How To: Get Started with the Open Graph | publisher=Facebook | date=2011-09-23 }}</ref>  The platform offers a set of [[API|programming interfaces]] and tools which enable developers to integrate with the open \"[[social graph]]\" of personal relations and other things like songs, places, and Facebook pages. Allocation the on facebook.com, external websites, and devices are all allowed to access the graph.\n\n==History==\nFacebook launched the Facebook Platform on <time datetime=\"2007-05-24\">May 24, 2007</time>, providing a [[software framework|framework]] for [[software developer]]s to create [[application software|applications]] that interact with core [[List of Facebook features|Facebook features]].<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|access-date=2008-03-05|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/24/technology/facebook.fortune/|title=Facebook's plan to hook up the world|publisher=CNN|date=2007-05-29|author=Kirkpatrick, David|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226142813/http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/24/technology/facebook.fortune/|archive-date=2008-02-26|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"F8\"/> A [[markup language]] called Facebook Markup Language was introduced simultaneously; it is used to customize the \"look and feel\" of applications that developers create. Prior to the Facebook platform, Facebook had built many applications themselves within the Facebook website, including Gifts, allowing users to send virtual gifts to each other, [[Facebook features#Marketplace|Marketplace]], allowing users to post free classified ads, Facebook events, giving users a method of informing their friends about upcoming events, [[Facebook features#Videos|Video]], letting users share homemade videos with one another,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-05-03|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070705.wgtfacebook05/BNStory/Technology/|title=Facebook users embracing the Marketplace |work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2007-07-05|author=George-Cosh, David|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-05-03|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/132245-1/article.html?tk=nl_dnxnws|title=Facebook Launches Video System |work=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]|date=2007-05-25|author=Schwankert, Steven }}</ref> and [[social network game]], where users can use their connections to friends to help them advance in games they are playing. The Facebook Platform made it possible for outside partners to build similar applications.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"F8\" /> Many of the popular early social network games would combine capabilities. For instance, one of the early games to reach the top application spot, [[(Lil) Green Patch]], combined virtual Gifts with Event notifications to friends and contributions to charities through Causes.\n\nThird party companies provide application metrics, and several [[blog]]s arose in response to the clamor for Facebook applications. On <time datetime=\"2007-07-04\">July 4, 2007</time>, Altura Ventures announced the \"Altura 1 Facebook Investment Fund,\" becoming the world's first Facebook-only venture capital firm.<ref name=Altura>{{cite news | url=http://www.altura.com/ | title=Altura Ventures news | publisher=Altura Ventures | date=2007-07-04 | accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref>\n\nOn <time datetime=\"2007-08-29\">August 29, 2007</time>, Facebook changed the way in which the popularity of applications is measured, to give attention to the more engaging applications, following criticism that ranking applications only by the number of people who had installed the application was giving an advantage to the highly viral, yet useless applications.<ref name=Facebook>{{cite news | first=Dave | last=Morin | url=https://www.facebook.com/developers/ | title=A shift to engagement | publisher=Facebook | date=2007-08-29 | accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref>\nTech blog [[Valleywag]] has criticized Facebook Applications, labeling them a \"cornucopia of uselessness.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Can a Facebook app possibly be useful? \n |publisher=Valleywag.com \n |date=2005-09-26 \n |url=http://gawker.com/303819/can-a-facebook-app-possibly-be-useful \n |access-date=2007-10-16 \n |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6HbEbJIqz?url=http://gawker.com/303819/can-a-facebook-app-possibly-be-useful \n |archive-date=2013-06-23\n |url-status=dead \n |df= \n}}</ref> Others have called for limiting third-party applications so the Facebook [[user experience]] is not degraded.<ref>{{cite web |access-date=2008-03-05 |url=http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2007/12/03/Campus/Useless.Applications.Plague.Facebook-3128521.shtml |title=Useless applications plague Facebook |publisher=The Lantern |author=Timmons, Zack |date=2007-12-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309120240/http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2007/12/03/Campus/Useless.Applications.Plague.Facebook-3128521.shtml |archive-date=2008-03-09 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://techdirt.com/articles/20071130/110033.shtml|title=Irritating Your Customers Is Almost Never A Good Business Strategy|accessdate=2008-03-05|date=2007-11-30|author=Lee, Tim}}</ref>\n\nApplications that have been created on the Platform include [[chess]], which both allow users to play games with their friends.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-15|url=https://www.facebook.com/apps/application.php?id=2427617054&ref=s|title=Chess |publisher=Facebook}}</ref> In such games, a user's moves are saved on the website, allowing the next move to be made at any time rather than immediately after the previous move.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-03-15|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2007/11/20/BU5LTFF6N.DTL&type=business|title=Mountain View startup Meebo aims to revolutionize instant messaging |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | first=Ryan | last=Kim |date=2007-11-20}}</ref>\n\nBy <time datetime=\"2007-11-03\">November 3, 2007</time>, seven thousand applications had been developed on the Facebook Platform, with another hundred created every day.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-05-07|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/02/AR2007110201894_pf.html|title=Widgets Become Coins of the Social Realm |work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2007-11-03|author=[[Catherine Rampell|Rampell, Catherine]]|page=D01 }}</ref> By the [[Facebook f8|second annual f8]] developers conference on <time datetime=\"2008-07-23\">July 23, 2008</time>, the number of applications had grown to 33,000,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/07/23/BU7C11TAES.DTL |title=Developers compete at Facebook conference |accessdate=2008-08-14 |last=Ustinova |first=Anastasia |date=2008-07-23 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher= |doi= |quote= }}</ref> and the number of registered developers had exceeded 400,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/press/releases.php?p=48242 |title=Facebook Expands Power of Platform Across the Web and Around the World |accessdate=2008-08-14 |date=2008-07-23 |publisher=Facebook |doi= |quote= }}</ref>\n\nWithin a few months of launching the Facebook Platform, issues arose regarding \"application [[spam (electronic)|spam]]\", which involves Facebook applications \"spamming\" users to request it be installed.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-03-15| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/29/AR2007082900041_pf.html|title=Facebook cracks down on developer spam |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nFacebook integration was announced for the [[Xbox 360]] and [[Nintendo DSi]] on <time datetime=\"2007-06-01\">June 1, 2009</time> at E3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neelscompany.com/e3-2009-fun-friends-biggest-social-network-planet/ |title=Microsoft E3 Announcement |publisher=Neelscompany.com |date=2015-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208161155/http://www.neelscompany.com/e3-2009-fun-friends-biggest-social-network-planet/ |archive-date=2015-02-08 |df= }}</ref> On <time datetime=\"2009-11-18\">November 18, 2009</time>, Sony announced an integration with Facebook to deliver the first phase of a variety of new features to further connect and enhance the online social experiences of PlayStation 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/104/1046814p1.html |title=Sony to Offer Richer Online Social Experience to PS3 Owners With Facebook Integration|publisher=ign.com |date=2009-11-18 |accessdate=2010-05-06}}</ref> On <time datetime=\"2010-02-02\">February 2, 2010</time>, Facebook announced the release of ''[[HipHop for PHP]]'' as an opensource project.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kincaid|first=Jason|title=Live From Facebook's HipHop Technology Tasting|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/02/facebook-hiphop-presentation/|work=techcrunch.com|publisher=\u00a9 2010 TechCrunch|accessdate=6 July 2010}}</ref>\nMark Zuckerberg said that his team from Facebook is developing a Facebook search engine.<ref>[http://searchfortechnology.com/facebook-is-developing-its-own-search-engine/ Facebook is developing its own Search Engine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011050827/http://searchfortechnology.com/facebook-is-developing-its-own-search-engine/ |date=October 11, 2012 }}. Search for technology (2012-09-17). Retrieved on 2013-07-24.</ref> \u201cFacebook is pretty well placed to respond to people\u2019s questions. At some point, we will. We have a team that is working on it\", said Mark Zuckerberg. For him, the traditional search engines return too many results that do not necessarily respond to questions. \u201cThe search engines really need to evolve a set of answers: 'I have a specific question, answer this question for me.'\"\n\nOn <time datetime=\"2014-06-10\">June 10, 2014</time>, Facebook announced Haxl, a Haskell library that simplified the access to remote data, such as databases or web-based services.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2014-06-10| url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/302060973291128/open-sourcing-haxl-a-library-for-haskell/|title=Open-sourcing Haxl, a library for Haskell |work=Facebook Code}}</ref>\n\n===Partnerships with device manufacturers===\n\nStarting in 2007, Facebook formed [[data sharing]] partnerships with at least 60 handset manufacturers, including [[Apple (company)|Apple]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[BlackBerry]], [[Microsoft]] and [[Samsung]].<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\">{{cite news |last1=Dance |first1=Gabriel J.X. |last2=Confessore |first2=Nicholas |last3=LaForgia |first3=Michael |title=Facebook Gave Device Makers Deep Access to Data on Users and Friends |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/03/technology/facebook-device-partners-users-friends-data.html |accessdate=August 13, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2018}}</ref> Those manufacturers were provided with Facebook user data without the users' consent.<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/> Most of the partnerships remained in place as of 2018, when the partnerships were first publicly reported.<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/>\n\n==High-level Platform components==\n\n===Graph API===\nThe Graph API is the core of Facebook Platform, enabling developers to read from and write data into Facebook. The Graph API presents a simple, consistent view of the Facebook social graph, uniformly representing objects in the graph (e.g., people, photos, events, and pages) and the connections between them (e.g., friend relationships, shared content, and photo tags).<ref name=\"Graph API\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/api|title=Graph API}}</ref>\n\n===Authentication===\nFacebook authentication enables developers\u2019 applications to interact with the Graph API on behalf of Facebook users, and it provides a single-sign on mechanism across web, mobile, and desktop apps.<ref name=\"Authentication\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/authentication/|title=Authentication}}</ref>\n\n===Social plugins===\nSocial plugins \u2013 including the [[Like Button]], Recommendations, and Activity Feed \u2013 enable developers to provide social experiences to their users with just a few lines of HTML. All social plugins are extensions of Facebook and are designed so that no user data is shared with the sites on which they appear.<ref name=\"Social plugins\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/plugins |title=Social Plugins |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621235043/http://developers.facebook.com/plugins |archive-date=2010-06-21 |df= }}</ref> On the other hand, the social plugins let Facebook track its users\u2019 browsing habits through any sites that feature the plugins.\n\n===Open Graph protocol===\n[[File:Open Graph protocol logo.png|thumb|120px|Open Graph protocol logo]]\nThe Open Graph protocol enables developers to integrate their pages into Facebook's global mapping/tracking tool [[Social Graph]]. These pages gain the functionality of other graph objects including profile links and stream updates for connected users.<ref name=\"Open Graph protocol\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/opengraph|title=Open Graph Protocol}}</ref>  OpenGraph tags in [[HTML5]] might look like this:\n<source lang=\"XML\" enclose=\"div\">\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Example title of article\">\n<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"example.com website\">\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\">\n<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"http://example.com/example-title-of-article\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"http://example.com/article_thumbnail.jpg\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"http://example.com/website_logo.png\">\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"This example article is an example of OpenGraph protocol.\">\n</source>\n\n===iframes===\nFacebook uses [[iframes]] to allow third-party developers to create applications that are hosted separately from Facebook, but operate within a Facebook session and are accessed through a user's profile. Since iframes essentially nest independent websites within a Facebook session, their content is distinct from Facebook formatting.\n\nFacebook originally used 'Facebook Markup Language (FBML)' to allow [[Facebook features#Applications|Facebook Application]] [[software developer|developers]] to customize the \"look and feel\" of their [[Application software|applications]], to a limited extent. FBML is a [[specification]] of how to encode content so that Facebook's [[Server (computing)|servers]] can read and publish it, which is needed in the Facebook-specific feed so that Facebook's system can properly parse content and publish it as specified.<ref name=Acce125>{{cite press release|publisher=Mashery|date=2007-05-26|title='''Facebook Markup Language - A \"Reverse API\"'''|url=http://oren.blogs.com/praxis/2007/05/facebook_markup.html}}</ref> FBML set by any application is cached by Facebook until a subsequent API call replaces it. Facebook also offers a specialized Facebook JavaScript (FBJS) library.<ref name=\"FBJS\">{{cite web|url=http://wiki.developers.facebook.com/index.php/FBJS |title=FBJS |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223061112/http://wiki.developers.facebook.com/index.php/FBJS |archive-date=2009-12-23 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFacebook stopped accepting new FBML applications on <time datetime=\"2011-03-18\">March 18, 2011</time>,<ref name=\"FBMLdeprecated_date\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/479|title=Platform Updates: Operation Developer Love|accessdate=16 May 2011|author=Nikolay Valtchanov}}</ref> but continued to support existing FBML tabs and applications.  Since <time datetime=\"2012-01-01\">January 1, 2012</time> FBML was no longer supported, and FBML no longer functioned as of <time datetime=\"2012-06-01\">June 1, 2012</time>.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Facebook Connect===\n'''Facebook Connect''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/2008/05/09/announcing-facebook-connect/ |title=Announcing Facebook Connect |publisher=Facebook.com |date=2008-05-09 |accessdate=2014-05-23}}</ref> also called '''Log in with Facebook''', like [[OpenID]], is a set of authentication [[Application programming interface|APIs]] from Facebook that developers can use to help their users connect and share with such users' Facebook friends (on and off Facebook) and increase engagement for their website or application.  When so used, Facebook members can log on to third-party websites, applications, mobile devices and gaming systems with their Facebook identity and, while logged in, can connect with friends via these media and post information and updates to their Facebook profile.\n\nOriginally unveiled during Facebook\u2019s developer conference, F8, in <time datetime=\"2008-07\">July 2008</time>, Log in with Facebook became generally available in <time datetime=\"2008-12\">December 2008</time>. According to an article from The New York Times, \"Some say the services are representative of surprising new thinking in Silicon Valley. Instead of trying to hoard information about their users, the Internet companies (including Facebook, Google, MySpace and Twitter) all share at least some of that data so people do not have to enter the same identifying information again and again on different sites.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/technology/internet/01facebook.html?_r=1&pagewanted=1&partner=rss&emc=rss NY Times]</ref>\n\nLog in with Facebook cannot be used by users in locations that cannot access Facebook, even if the third-party site is otherwise accessible from that location.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chester|first1=Ken|title=Censorship, external authentication, and other social media lessons from China's Great Firewall|url=https://www.techinasia.com/china-social-media-lessons-from-great-firewall/|accessdate=4 June 2015|publisher=Tech in Asia|date=12 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Facebook, users who logged into ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' with Facebook spent more time on the site than the average user.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/by-the-numbers-how-facebook-says-likes-social-plugins-help-websites-76061 |title=By The Numbers: How Facebook Says Likes & Social Plugins Help Websites |author=[[Danny Sullivan (technologist)|Danny Sullivan]] |date=22 May 2011 |work=Search Engine Land }}</ref>\n\n===Microformats===\nIn <time datetime=\"2011-02\">February 2011</time>, Facebook began to use the [[hCalendar]] microformat to mark up events, and the [[hCard]] for the events' venues, enabling the extraction of details to users' own calendar or mapping applications.<ref name=\"Protagonist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/facebook/facebook-adds-hcalendar-and-hcard-microformats-to-events/266|title=Facebook adds and micro-formats to Events|last= linski|first=Emil|date=2011-02-18|publisher=ZDNet|accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Mobile platform===\nThe UI framework for the [[mobile website]] is based on [[Xhp]], the Javelin Javascript library, and [[WURFL]].<ref name=\"techprolonged mobile website\">{{cite web | url=http://techprolonged.com/index.php/2011/05/21/facebook-mobile-website-transition-issues/ | title=Facebook Mobile Website \u2013 Transition \u2013 Issues | publisher=techprolonged.com | date=May 21, 2011 | accessdate=December 29, 2011 | author=Ali, Khurram | quote=Facebook has mention in the note that the new website is powered by a UI framework based on XHP, Javelin and WURFL.}}</ref> The mobile platform has grown dramatically in popularity since its launch. In <time datetime=\"2012-12\">December 2012</time>, the number of users signing into the site from mobile devices exceeded web-based logins for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olanoff|first=Drew|title=For The First Time, Facebook's 680M Mobile MAUs Surpassed Desktop DAUs \u2014 Zuck Says It's Now A \"Mobile Company\"|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/01/30/for-the-first-time-facebook-mobile-daus-exceeded-web-daus-in-q4-2012/|publisher=Techcrunch|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=Jan 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2013}}\n\nMany Facebook application developers have attempted to create viral applications. [[Stanford University]] even offered a class in the Fall of <time>2007</time>, entitled Computer Science (CS) 377W: \"Create Engaging Web Applications Using Metrics and Learning on Facebook\". Numerous applications created by the class were highly successful, and ranked amongst the top Facebook applications, with some achieving over 3.5 million users in a month.<ref name=StanfordDaily>{{cite web | url=http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2007/11/30/farmmadeFacebookAppsPopular | title=Kamil Dada from Stanford University explains the success of Facebook applications developed in a class at Stanford University | author=Kamil Dada | date=2007-11-30 | access-date=2007-12-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080609020741/http://stanforddaily.com/article/2007/11/30/farmmadeFacebookAppsPopular |archive-date=June 9, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[The Guardian]]'' expressed concerns that users publishing content through a third party provider are exposed to losing their web positioning if their service is removed; and the open graph could force connecting web presence to Facebook social services even for people using their own publishing channels.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|publisher=The Guardian|title=Why Facebook's new Open Graph makes us all part of the web underclass|author=Adrian Short|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/sep/27/facebook-open-graph-web-underclass|location=London|date=2011-09-27}}</ref> In June 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' criticized Facebook's partnerships with device manufacturers, writing that the data available to these manufacturers \"raise concerns about the company's privacy protections and compliance with a 2011 consent decree with the Federal Trade Commission.\"<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Facebook features|Facebook features]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Online social networking}}\n{{Semantic Web}}\n\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2007]]\n[[Category:Federated identity]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = January 2019}}\n{{Short description|Application platform around Facebook's social network}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2019}}\n\nThe '''Facebook Platform''' is the set of services, tools, and products provided by the [[social networking service]] [[Facebook]] for [[third-party software component|third-party]] developers to create their own [[application software|applications]] and services that access data in Facebook.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\nThe current Facebook Platform was launched in <time>2010</time>.<ref name=\"F8\">{{cite news | url=https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/564/ | title=How To: Get Started with the Open Graph | publisher=Facebook | date=2011-09-23 }}</ref>  The platform offers a set of [[API|programming interfaces]] and tools which enable developers to integrate with the open \"[[social graph]]\" of personal relations and other things like songs, places, and Facebook pages. Allocation the on facebook.com, external websites, and devices are all allowed to access the graph.\n\n==History==\nFacebook launched the Facebook Platform on <time datetime=\"2007-05-24\">May 24, 2007</time>, providing a [[software framework|framework]] for [[software developer]]s to create [[application software|applications]] that interact with core [[List of Facebook features|Facebook features]].<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|access-date=2008-03-05|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/24/technology/facebook.fortune/|title=Facebook's plan to hook up the world|publisher=CNN|date=2007-05-29|author=Kirkpatrick, David|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226142813/http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/24/technology/facebook.fortune/|archive-date=2008-02-26|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"F8\"/> A [[markup language]] called Facebook Markup Language was introduced simultaneously; it is used to customize the \"look and feel\" of applications that developers create. Prior to the Facebook platform, Facebook had built many applications themselves within the Facebook website, including Gifts, allowing users to send virtual gifts to each other, [[Facebook features#Marketplace|Marketplace]], allowing users to post free classified ads, Facebook events, giving users a method of informing their friends about upcoming events, [[Facebook features#Videos|Video]], letting users share homemade videos with one another,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-05-03|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070705.wgtfacebook05/BNStory/Technology/|title=Facebook users embracing the Marketplace |work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2007-07-05|author=George-Cosh, David|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-05-03|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/132245-1/article.html?tk=nl_dnxnws|title=Facebook Launches Video System |work=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]|date=2007-05-25|author=Schwankert, Steven }}</ref> and [[social network game]], where users can use their connections to friends to help them advance in games they are playing. The Facebook Platform made it possible for outside partners to build similar applications.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"F8\" /> Many of the popular early social network games would combine capabilities. For instance, one of the early games to reach the top application spot, [[(Lil) Green Patch]], combined virtual Gifts with Event notifications to friends and contributions to charities through Causes.\n\nThird party companies provide application metrics, and several [[blog]]s arose in response to the clamor for Facebook applications. On <time datetime=\"2007-07-04\">July 4, 2007</time>, Altura Ventures announced the \"Altura 1 Facebook Investment Fund,\" becoming the world's first Facebook-only venture capital firm.<ref name=Altura>{{cite news | url=http://www.altura.com/ | title=Altura Ventures news | publisher=Altura Ventures | date=2007-07-04 | accessdate=2007-09-03}}</ref>\n\nOn <time datetime=\"2007-08-29\">August 29, 2007</time>, Facebook changed the way in which the popularity of applications is measured, to give attention to the more engaging applications, following criticism that ranking applications only by the number of people who had installed the application was giving an advantage to the highly viral, yet useless applications.<ref name=Facebook>{{cite news | first=Dave | last=Morin | url=https://www.facebook.com/developers/ | title=A shift to engagement | publisher=Facebook | date=2007-08-29 | accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref>\nTech blog [[Valleywag]] has criticized Facebook Applications, labeling them a \"cornucopia of uselessness.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Can a Facebook app possibly be useful? \n |publisher=Valleywag.com \n |date=2005-09-26 \n |url=http://gawker.com/303819/can-a-facebook-app-possibly-be-useful \n |access-date=2007-10-16 \n |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6HbEbJIqz?url=http://gawker.com/303819/can-a-facebook-app-possibly-be-useful \n |archive-date=2013-06-23\n |url-status=dead \n |df= \n}}</ref> Others have called for limiting third-party applications so the Facebook [[user experience]] is not degraded.<ref>{{cite web |access-date=2008-03-05 |url=http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2007/12/03/Campus/Useless.Applications.Plague.Facebook-3128521.shtml |title=Useless applications plague Facebook |publisher=The Lantern |author=Timmons, Zack |date=2007-12-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309120240/http://media.www.thelantern.com/media/storage/paper333/news/2007/12/03/Campus/Useless.Applications.Plague.Facebook-3128521.shtml |archive-date=2008-03-09 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://techdirt.com/articles/20071130/110033.shtml|title=Irritating Your Customers Is Almost Never A Good Business Strategy|accessdate=2008-03-05|date=2007-11-30|author=Lee, Tim}}</ref>\n\nApplications that have been created on the Platform include [[chess]], which both allow users to play games with their friends.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-03-15|url=https://www.facebook.com/apps/application.php?id=2427617054&ref=s|title=Chess |publisher=Facebook}}</ref> In such games, a user's moves are saved on the website, allowing the next move to be made at any time rather than immediately after the previous move.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-03-15|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2007/11/20/BU5LTFF6N.DTL&type=business|title=Mountain View startup Meebo aims to revolutionize instant messaging |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | first=Ryan | last=Kim |date=2007-11-20}}</ref>\n\nBy <time datetime=\"2007-11-03\">November 3, 2007</time>, seven thousand applications had been developed on the Facebook Platform, with another hundred created every day.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-05-07|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/02/AR2007110201894_pf.html|title=Widgets Become Coins of the Social Realm |work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2007-11-03|author=[[Catherine Rampell|Rampell, Catherine]]|page=D01 }}</ref> By the [[Facebook f8|second annual f8]] developers conference on <time datetime=\"2008-07-23\">July 23, 2008</time>, the number of applications had grown to 33,000,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/07/23/BU7C11TAES.DTL |title=Developers compete at Facebook conference |accessdate=2008-08-14 |last=Ustinova |first=Anastasia |date=2008-07-23 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher= |doi= |quote= }}</ref> and the number of registered developers had exceeded 400,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/press/releases.php?p=48242 |title=Facebook Expands Power of Platform Across the Web and Around the World |accessdate=2008-08-14 |date=2008-07-23 |publisher=Facebook |doi= |quote= }}</ref>\n\nWithin a few months of launching the Facebook Platform, issues arose regarding \"application [[spam (electronic)|spam]]\", which involves Facebook applications \"spamming\" users to request it be installed.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2008-03-15| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/29/AR2007082900041_pf.html|title=Facebook cracks down on developer spam |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nFacebook integration was announced for the [[Xbox 360]] and [[Nintendo DSi]] on <time datetime=\"2007-06-01\">June 1, 2009</time> at E3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neelscompany.com/e3-2009-fun-friends-biggest-social-network-planet/ |title=Microsoft E3 Announcement |publisher=Neelscompany.com |date=2015-02-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208161155/http://www.neelscompany.com/e3-2009-fun-friends-biggest-social-network-planet/ |archive-date=2015-02-08 |df= }}</ref> On <time datetime=\"2009-11-18\">November 18, 2009</time>, Sony announced an integration with Facebook to deliver the first phase of a variety of new features to further connect and enhance the online social experiences of PlayStation 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/104/1046814p1.html |title=Sony to Offer Richer Online Social Experience to PS3 Owners With Facebook Integration|publisher=ign.com |date=2009-11-18 |accessdate=2010-05-06}}</ref> On <time datetime=\"2010-02-02\">February 2, 2010</time>, Facebook announced the release of ''[[HipHop for PHP]]'' as an opensource project.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kincaid|first=Jason|title=Live From Facebook's HipHop Technology Tasting|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/02/facebook-hiphop-presentation/|work=techcrunch.com|publisher=\u00a9 2010 TechCrunch|accessdate=6 July 2010}}</ref>\nMark Zuckerberg said that his team from Facebook is developing a Facebook search engine.<ref>[http://searchfortechnology.com/facebook-is-developing-its-own-search-engine/ Facebook is developing its own Search Engine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011050827/http://searchfortechnology.com/facebook-is-developing-its-own-search-engine/ |date=October 11, 2012 }}. Search for technology (2012-09-17). Retrieved on 2013-07-24.</ref> \u201cFacebook is pretty well placed to respond to people\u2019s questions. At some point, we will. We have a team that is working on it\", said Mark Zuckerberg. For him, the traditional search engines return too many results that do not necessarily respond to questions. \u201cThe search engines really need to evolve a set of answers: 'I have a specific question, answer this question for me.'\"\n\nOn <time datetime=\"2014-06-10\">June 10, 2014</time>, Facebook announced Haxl, a Haskell library that simplified the access to remote data, such as databases or web-based services.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2014-06-10| url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/302060973291128/open-sourcing-haxl-a-library-for-haskell/|title=Open-sourcing Haxl, a library for Haskell |work=Facebook Code}}</ref>\n\n===Partnerships with device manufacturers===\n\nStarting in 2007, Facebook formed [[data sharing]] partnerships with at least 60 handset manufacturers, including [[Apple (company)|Apple]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[BlackBerry]], [[Microsoft]] and [[Samsung]].<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\">{{cite news |last1=Dance |first1=Gabriel J.X. |last2=Confessore |first2=Nicholas |last3=LaForgia |first3=Michael |title=Facebook Gave Device Makers Deep Access to Data on Users and Friends |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/03/technology/facebook-device-partners-users-friends-data.html |accessdate=August 13, 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2018}}</ref> Those manufacturers were provided with Facebook user data without the users' consent.<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/> Most of the partnerships remained in place as of 2018, when the partnerships were first publicly reported.<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/>\n\n==High-level Platform components==\n\n===Graph API===\nThe Graph API is the core of Facebook Platform, enabling developers to read from and write data into Facebook. The Graph API presents a simple, consistent view of the Facebook social graph, uniformly representing objects in the graph (e.g., people, photos, events, and pages) and the connections between them (e.g., friend relationships, shared content, and photo tags).<ref name=\"Graph API\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/api|title=Graph API}}</ref>\n\n===Authentication===\nFacebook authentication enables developers\u2019 applications to interact with the Graph API on behalf of Facebook users, and it provides a single-sign on mechanism across web, mobile, and desktop apps.<ref name=\"Authentication\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/authentication/|title=Authentication}}</ref>\n\n===Social plugins===\nSocial plugins \u2013 including the [[Like Button]], Recommendations, and Activity Feed \u2013 enable developers to provide social experiences to their users with just a few lines of HTML. All social plugins are extensions of Facebook and are designed so that no user data is shared with the sites on which they appear.<ref name=\"Social plugins\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/plugins |title=Social Plugins |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621235043/http://developers.facebook.com/plugins |archive-date=2010-06-21 |df= }}</ref> On the other hand, the social plugins let Facebook track its users\u2019 browsing habits through any sites that feature the plugins.\n\n===Open Graph protocol===\n[[File:Open Graph protocol logo.png|thumb|120px|Open Graph protocol logo]]\nThe Open Graph protocol enables developers to integrate their pages into Facebook's global mapping/tracking tool [[Social Graph]]. These pages gain the functionality of other graph objects including profile links and stream updates for connected users.<ref name=\"Open Graph protocol\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/docs/opengraph|title=Open Graph Protocol}}</ref>  OpenGraph tags in [[HTML5]] might look like this:\n<source lang=\"XML\" enclose=\"div\">\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Example title of article\">\n<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"example.com website\">\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\">\n<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"http://example.com/example-title-of-article\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"http://example.com/article_thumbnail.jpg\">\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"http://example.com/website_logo.png\">\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"This example article is an example of OpenGraph protocol.\">\n</source>\n\n===iframes===\nFacebook uses [[iframes]] to allow third-party developers to create applications that are hosted separately from Facebook, but operate within a Facebook session and are accessed through a user's profile. Since iframes essentially nest independent websites within a Facebook session, their content is distinct from Facebook formatting.\n\nFacebook originally used 'Facebook Markup Language (FBML)' to allow [[Facebook features#Applications|Facebook Application]] [[software developer|developers]] to customize the \"look and feel\" of their [[Application software|applications]], to a limited extent. FBML is a [[specification]] of how to encode content so that Facebook's [[Server (computing)|servers]] can read and publish it, which is needed in the Facebook-specific feed so that Facebook's system can properly parse content and publish it as specified.<ref name=Acce125>{{cite press release|publisher=Mashery|date=2007-05-26|title='''Facebook Markup Language - A \"Reverse API\"'''|url=http://oren.blogs.com/praxis/2007/05/facebook_markup.html}}</ref> FBML set by any application is cached by Facebook until a subsequent API call replaces it. Facebook also offers a specialized Facebook JavaScript (FBJS) library.<ref name=\"FBJS\">{{cite web|url=http://wiki.developers.facebook.com/index.php/FBJS |title=FBJS |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223061112/http://wiki.developers.facebook.com/index.php/FBJS |archive-date=2009-12-23 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFacebook stopped accepting new FBML applications on <time datetime=\"2011-03-18\">March 18, 2011</time>,<ref name=\"FBMLdeprecated_date\">{{cite web|url=http://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/479|title=Platform Updates: Operation Developer Love|accessdate=16 May 2011|author=Nikolay Valtchanov}}</ref> but continued to support existing FBML tabs and applications.  Since <time datetime=\"2012-01-01\">January 1, 2012</time> FBML was no longer supported, and FBML no longer functioned as of <time datetime=\"2012-06-01\">June 1, 2012</time>.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\n===Facebook Connect===\n'''Facebook Connect''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/2008/05/09/announcing-facebook-connect/ |title=Announcing Facebook Connect |publisher=Facebook.com |date=2008-05-09 |accessdate=2014-05-23}}</ref> also called '''Log in with Facebook''', like [[OpenID]], is a set of authentication [[Application programming interface|APIs]] from Facebook that developers can use to help their users connect and share with such users' Facebook friends (on and off Facebook) and increase engagement for their website or application.  When so used, Facebook members can log on to third-party websites, applications, mobile devices and gaming systems with their Facebook identity and, while logged in, can connect with friends via these media and post information and updates to their Facebook profile.\n\nOriginally unveiled during Facebook\u2019s developer conference, F8, in <time datetime=\"2008-07\">July 2008</time>, Log in with Facebook became generally available in <time datetime=\"2008-12\">December 2008</time>. According to an article from The New York Times, \"Some say the services are representative of surprising new thinking in Silicon Valley. Instead of trying to hoard information about their users, the Internet companies (including Facebook, Google, MySpace and Twitter) all share at least some of that data so people do not have to enter the same identifying information again and again on different sites.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/01/technology/internet/01facebook.html?_r=1&pagewanted=1&partner=rss&emc=rss NY Times]</ref>\n\nLog in with Facebook cannot be used by users in locations that cannot access Facebook, even if the third-party site is otherwise accessible from that location.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chester|first1=Ken|title=Censorship, external authentication, and other social media lessons from China's Great Firewall|url=https://www.techinasia.com/china-social-media-lessons-from-great-firewall/|accessdate=4 June 2015|publisher=Tech in Asia|date=12 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Facebook, users who logged into ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' with Facebook spent more time on the site than the average user.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/by-the-numbers-how-facebook-says-likes-social-plugins-help-websites-76061 |title=By The Numbers: How Facebook Says Likes & Social Plugins Help Websites |author=[[Danny Sullivan (technologist)|Danny Sullivan]] |date=22 May 2011 |work=Search Engine Land }}</ref>\n\n===Microformats===\nIn <time datetime=\"2011-02\">February 2011</time>, Facebook began to use the [[hCalendar]] microformat to mark up events, and the [[hCard]] for the events' venues, enabling the extraction of details to users' own calendar or mapping applications.<ref name=\"Protagonist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/facebook/facebook-adds-hcalendar-and-hcard-microformats-to-events/266|title=Facebook adds and micro-formats to Events|last= linski|first=Emil|date=2011-02-18|publisher=ZDNet|accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Mobile platform===\nThe UI framework for the [[mobile website]] is based on [[Xhp]], the Javelin Javascript library, and [[WURFL]].<ref name=\"techprolonged mobile website\">{{cite web | url=http://techprolonged.com/index.php/2011/05/21/facebook-mobile-website-transition-issues/ | title=Facebook Mobile Website \u2013 Transition \u2013 Issues | publisher=techprolonged.com | date=May 21, 2011 | accessdate=December 29, 2011 | author=Ali, Khurram | quote=Facebook has mention in the note that the new website is powered by a UI framework based on XHP, Javelin and WURFL.}}</ref> The mobile platform has grown dramatically in popularity since its launch. In <time datetime=\"2012-12\">December 2012</time>, the number of users signing into the site from mobile devices exceeded web-based logins for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olanoff|first=Drew|title=For The First Time, Facebook's 680M Mobile MAUs Surpassed Desktop DAUs \u2014 Zuck Says It's Now A \"Mobile Company\"|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/01/30/for-the-first-time-facebook-mobile-daus-exceeded-web-daus-in-q4-2012/|publisher=Techcrunch|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=Jan 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2013}}\n\nMany Facebook application developers have attempted to create viral applications. [[Stanford University]] even offered a class in the Fall of <time>2007</time>, entitled Computer Science (CS) 377W: \"Create Engaging Web Applications Using Metrics and Learning on Facebook\". Numerous applications created by the class were highly successful, and ranked amongst the top Facebook applications, with some achieving over 3.5 million users in a month.<ref name=StanfordDaily>{{cite web | url=http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2007/11/30/farmmadeFacebookAppsPopular | title=Kamil Dada from Stanford University explains the success of Facebook applications developed in a class at Stanford University | author=Kamil Dada | date=2007-11-30 | access-date=2007-12-15|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080609020741/http://stanforddaily.com/article/2007/11/30/farmmadeFacebookAppsPopular |archive-date=June 9, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, ''[[The Guardian]]'' expressed concerns that users publishing content through a third party provider are exposed to losing their web positioning if their service is removed; and the open graph could force connecting web presence to Facebook social services even for people using their own publishing channels.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|publisher=The Guardian|title=Why Facebook's new Open Graph makes us all part of the web underclass|author=Adrian Short|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/sep/27/facebook-open-graph-web-underclass|location=London|date=2011-09-27}}</ref> In June 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' criticized Facebook's partnerships with device manufacturers, writing that the data available to these manufacturers \"raise concerns about the company's privacy protections and compliance with a 2011 consent decree with the Federal Trade Commission.\"<ref name=\"nyt-2018-06-03\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Facebook features]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Online social networking}}\n{{Semantic Web}}\n\n[[Category:Facebook]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2007]]\n[[Category:Federated identity]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n", "name_user": "AngelaCaptaingamer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial plugins", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Facebook_Platform"}
{"title_page": "Dalej jest noc", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{missing information|the content of the book|date=August 2019}}\n{{italics title}}\n'''''Dalej jest noc: losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski''''' (\"Night without End: The Fate of Jews in Selected Counties of Occupied Poland\"), co-edited by [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]] and [[Barbara Engelking]], is a two-volume study published in 2018 by the [[Polish Center for Holocaust Research]] in [[Warsaw, Poland]]. The 1,600-page study contains nine chapters, each covering a county in [[occupied Poland]] in 1939\u20131945\u2014[[Bielsk County|Bielsk Podlaski]], [[Bi\u0142goraj County|Bi\u0142goraj]], [[Bochnia County|Bochnia]], [[D\u0119bica County|D\u0119bica]], [[\u0141uk\u00f3w County|Luk\u00f3w]], [[Miech\u00f3w County|Miech\u00f3w]], [[Nowy Targ County|Nowy Targ]], [[W\u0119gr\u00f3w County|W\u0119gr\u00f3w]], and [[Z\u0142ocz\u00f3w]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski |url=https://www.academia.edu/37020664/Dalej_jest_noc._Losy_%C5%BByd%C3%B3w_w_wybranych_powiatach_okupowanej_Polski_Night_without_End_The_Fate_of_Jews_in_Selected_Counties_of_Occupied_Poland_2018_ |website=Academia.edu}}</ref>\u2014in the [[General Government]] area established by Germany in [[World War II]]. The study identifies small Polish towns as \"death traps\" for Jews in hiding.<ref name=\"JTA20180511\">[https://www.jta.org/2018/05/11/default/poles-helped-kill-jews-hiding-nazis-study-claims Study says Polish neighbors betrayed many more Jews than previously thought], [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], 11 May 2018.</ref> An abridged English-language version of the study is forthcoming.<ref name=\"Frydel\">[https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14623528.2018.1527091?journalCode=cjgr20 Frydel, Tomasz. \"The Ongoing Challenge of Producing an Integrated Microhistory of the Holocaust in East Central Europe.\" Journal of Genocide Research 20.4 (2018): 624\u2013631.]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nSeveral scholars, mainly associated with [[Poland]]'s [[Institute of National Remembrance]], have criticized ''Dalej jest noc'' for using unreliable sources, for ignoring the context of Germany's draconian occupation policies and practices, for some  authors' alleged personal interests, for selective treatment of witness statements (questioning Polish witnesses' statements, while taking at face value witness statements that were in line with authors' theses), and for presenting rumors and gossip as actual proven facts.<ref>Tomasz Doma\u0144ski,  [https://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/241621/Korektaobrazu.pdf ''\"Korekta obrazu? Refleksje \u017ar\u00f3d\u0142oznawcze wok\u00f3\u0142 ksi\u0105\u017cki ''Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski\" (\"A Corrected Picture?  Reflections on Use of Sources in the Book, ''Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski''\"], [[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]], ''[[Polish-Jewish Studies]]'', 2019, 72 pp.</ref><ref name=Roguski/><ref>[https://www.dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/ukazaly-sie-kolejne-trzy-recenzje-ipn-na-temat-publikacji-dalej-jest-noc] ''\"Ukaza\u0142y si\u0119 kolejne trzy recenzje IPN na temat publikacji'' [Three More [[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]] Reviews Have Appeared of] ''Dalej jest noc\"'', Dzieje.pl 21.02.19.</ref><ref>[[Dawid Golik]], ''\"Nowatorska noc. Kilka uwag na marginesie artyku\u0142u Karoliny Panz\"'' [\"Innovative Night:  Some Remarks about [[Karolina Panz]]'s Article\"], ''Zeszyty Historyczne WiN-u'' ''nr'' [no.] 47, 2018, pp. 109\u201334.</ref><ref>[[Jacek Borkowicz]], \"[https://www.rp.pl/Kraj/302109970-Wraca-spor-o-udzial-w-Zagladzie.html] ''\"Wraca sp\u00f3r o zag\u0142adzie\"'' [\"Argument over Genocide Returns\"], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 February 2019.</ref> \nHistorian [[Jacek Borkowicz]] writes in the Polish newspaper ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' that, using data from the book, he concludes that the actual number of Jewish victims of Poles was much lower, at most 40,000, while around 50,000 and possibly as many as 100,000 Jews were saved by Poles.<ref>[https://www.rp.pl/Plus-Minus/305179916-Pogruchotana-pamiec-o-Zagladzie.html] [[Jacek Borkowicz]], ''\"Pogruchotana pami\u0119\u0107 o Zag\u0142adzie\"'' [\"Mangled Memory of Genocide\"], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]: Plus Minus'', 17 May 2018.</ref> Tomasz Doma\u0144ski writes in ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' that the authors speak of a \"Polish-German administration\", whereas there was no Polish administration in German-occupied territories, and that the authors' use of materials is tendentiously selective. He also criticizes the misleading use of the expression \"Polish Police\" (the [[Blue Police]] was a German-run entity based on conscripted prewar Polish police officers) and the lack of a common definition of \"county\".<ref>[https://www.rp.pl/Kraj/302109970-Wraca-spor-o-udzial-w-Zagladzie.html] Wraca spor o udzial w Zagladzie</ref>\n\nHistorian [[Piotr Gontarczyk]] charges the book with \"scholarly mystification\". As an example of gross inaccuracy, Gontarczyk gives the book's description of events in the [[Bochnia Ghetto]] in German-occupied Poland. Gontarczyk writes that the book \"makes the [[Jewish Ghetto Police]] disappear, replacing it with Polish police.\"  The Bochnia Ghetto, he says, witnessed \"[[Inferno (Dante)|scenes out of Dante]], with the participation of the [[Jewish Ghetto Police]] (''J\u00fcdische Ordnungstdienst''); there were no ''Polish'' police [inside Jewish ghettos], but the book... says the bunkers [in which some Jews hid, hoping to escape deportation to German extermination camps] were searched by ''Polish'' police.\"<ref>[[Piotr Gontarczyk]],  ''[http://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/246298/GontarczykGlaukopis36.pdf \"Mi\u0119dzy nauk\u0105 a mistyfikacj\u0105, czyli o naturze pi\u015bmiennictwa prof. Jana Grabowskiego na podstawie casusu wsi Wrotn\u00f3w i Mi\u0119dzyle\u015b powiatu w\u0119growskiego\" (''\"Between Scholarship and Mystification:  On the Nature of Professor Jan Grabowski's Writings, Based on the Cases of the Villages of Wrotn\u00f3w and Mi\u0119dzyle\u015b in [[W\u0119gr\u00f3w County]]\"''), Glaukopis, ''no. 36, pp. 313\u2013323.'']</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.polskieradio.pl/321/1222/Artykul/2275685,Piotr-Gontarczyk-zarzuca-publikacji-Centrum-Badan-nad-Zaglada-Zydow-naukowa-mistyfikacje |title = Piotr Gontarczyk zarzuca publikacji Centrum Bada\u0144 nad Zag\u0142ad\u0105 \u017byd\u00f3w \"naukow\u0105 mistyfikacj\u0119\"  |publisher = polskieradio.pl |date = 10 March 2019 |access-date = 10 March 2019 |language= pl}}</ref> One of the book's authors, [[Dagmara Swa\u0142tek-Niewi\u0144ska]] has replied that Gontarczyk is incorrect, and that the book discusses the Jewish Ghetto Police in numerous places, and she in turn charges Gontarczyk with not having read the book thoroughly and with drawing incorrect conclusions from a cursory reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wyborcza.pl/alehistoria/7,121681,24574550,piotr-gontarczyk-i-tygodnik-sieci-zlapani-na-klamstwie-czyli.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Piotr Gontarczyk i tygodnik \"Sieci\" z\u0142apani na k\u0142amstwie, czyli nowa szko\u0142a polemiki o Zag\u0142adzie|last=Swa\u0142tek-Niewi\u0144ska|first=Dagmara|date=22 March 2019|website=wyborcza.pl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nHistorian {{ill|Jacek Chrobaczy\u0144ski|pl|Jacek Chrobaczy\u0144ski}} writes that the study is based on solid analysis of sources. He notes the naming of perpetrators and co-perpetrators \u2013 individuals who took over Jewish property \u2013 and participation by the Polish [[Blue Police]], [[Baudienst]], fire brigades, and military guards. He writes that the study is important in deconstructing some political myths and propaganda in Polish history writing, journalism,  church pronouncements, and politics. He concludes that the two volumes are \"solid and reliable scholarship\".<ref>[http://resgestae.up.krakow.pl/article/download/4604/4323 Chrobaczy\u0144ski, Jacek. \"Osaczeni, samotni, bezbronni... Refleksje po lekturze ksi\u0105\u017cki Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski (Polish with English abstract), T. I, II, pod redakcj\u0105 Barbary Engelking i Jana Grabowskiego, Warszawa 2018.\" Res Gestae 6 (2018): 266\u2013301.]</ref>\n\n[[Karolina Koprowska]], writes that the book focuses on micro-history studies and case-study analysis. She calls it a unique book with both a clear scholarly goal and a political message, taking a clear stance in the ongoing discussion in Poland about Polish-Jewish historical relations. She writes that the book is valuable for its solid methodology, rare and personal focus on micro-history, and demonstration of how significant were varying local characteristics, which resulted in widely different and not fully generalizable circumstances that Jews faced in different parts of occupied Poland. She does note that the book may, however, lack an overarching methodological conclusion and does not attempt a new grand theory of Polish-Jewish wartime history.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koprowska|first=Karolina|date=2018|title=Nocne i dzienne historie: do\u015bwiadczenie Zag\u0142ady na polskiej prowincji. (O ksi\u0105\u017cce \u201eDalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski\u201d)|url=https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=786184|journal=Wielog\u0142os|language=Polish|issue=36|pages=161\u2013174|issn=1897-1962}}</ref>\n\n[[Beth Holmgren]] writes that ''Dalej jest noc'' is a \"highly detailed, systematically organized, data-based analysis of how and by whom the [[Holocaust]] was perpetrated in nine separate Polish counties\".<ref>Holmgren, Beth. \"Holocaust History and Jewish Heritage Preservation: Scholars and Stewards Working in PiS-Ruled Poland.\" Shofar 37.1 (2019): 96\u2013107.</ref>\n\n[[Tomasz Roguski]]'s review of the book focuses particularly on the chapter by [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]]. Roguski writes that the book deals with an interesting topic that needs further research. He commends the authors for pioneering work but criticizes some of its methodology, its use of some primary sources to the neglect of others, its too narrow focus, and its statistical conclusions.<ref name=Roguski>Tomasz Roguski, ''[http://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/244267/RoguskiDalejjestnocGlaukopis36.pdf \"Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski, red. Barbara Engelking i Jan Grabowski\", Glaukopis, ''no. 36, pp. 335\u2013356.'']</ref>\n\n==Missing [[Bielsko County]] chapter==\nPolish historian and [[religion|religions scholar]] [[Jacek Proszyk]] had been asked to work up [[Bielsko County]] for ''Dalej jest noc''.  However, he was unable to submit a finished text, largely because of methodological difficulties that he encountered. He \"[found it impossible to obtain] data sufficiently reliable to... perform statistical analysis and [to determine] the exact number of persons who perished, the exact number... who survived, and how they survived.\"  Proszyk concluded that he could only \"describe... verified individual cases.  The war\", he writes, \"was a great DESTRUCTION and LIE.  We do not have... complete archival records....  Even what we have is not always the truth.... [I]n Bielsko and Bia\u0142a [which were only part of the county that Proszyk was to have covered, in order to survive] Jews, Poles, and [anti-Nazi] Germans [all had to flee, lie, or pretend to be what they were not].  This falsehood left its [imprint] in the records and accounts, and that is why I [felt compelled] to verify... every account and every entry.\"  Proszyk was unable to submit generalized findings for Bielsko County, but he hopes to eventually prepare a study of particular individuals' experiences there. Proszyk's experience highlights the methodological difficulties in undertaking a reliable study of such subject matter.<ref>[[Jacek Proszyk]], ''\"Nienapisany rozdzia\u0142. Powiat bielski (Wschodni G\u00f3rny \u015al\u0105sk), niem. Landkreis Bielitz, Ost-Oberschlesien\"'' [\"Unwritten Chapter:  [[Bielsko County]] (Eastern [[Upper Silesia]]), [[German language|German]]:  ''Landkreis Bielitz, Ost-Oberschlesien''\"], ''Jacek Proszyk \u2013 w\u0142asne zapiski'' ([[Jacek Proszyk]]: Personal Notes), 21 May 2018.  [http://proszyk.blogspot.com/2018/05/nienapisany-rozdzia-powiat-bielski.html]</ref>\n\n==Litigation against editors==\n''Dalej jest noc'' accuses Edward Malinowski, ''so\u0142tys'' of the Polish village of Malinowo, of having been responsible for the deaths of dozens of Jews who, during World War II, were in hiding from the Germans. His 94-year-old relative Filomena Leszczy\u0144ska is suing Professors Engelking and Grabowski, the book's editors, in Warsaw court for defaming Malinowski, asserting that, on the contrary, he had assisted Jews, at the risk of his own life and the lives of his family.<ref>[https://www.tvp.info/42706332/pozew-przeciwko-engelking-i-grabowskiemu-zarzut-publikacja-zmyslonych-informacji] S\u0142awomir Cedzy\u0144ski, ''\"Pozew przeciwko Engelking i Grabowskiemu.  Zarzut:  publikacja zmy\u015blonych informacji\"'' (\"Court Summons for Engelking and Grabowski.  The Charge:  Publication of Fabricated Information\"), ''TVP INFO'', 20 May 2019.</ref><ref>[http://rdi.org.pl/] \"The RDI [Polish League against Defamation] Backs the Family of Edward Malinowski in Their Lawsuit against Prof. [[Barbara Engelking]] and Dr. [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]]\", [[Polish League Against Defamation|Polish League against Defamation]], 21 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Hunt for the Jews]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:History books about the Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Books about Jewish Polish history]]\n[[Category:Polish-language books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{missing information|the content of the book|date=August 2019}}\n{{italics title}}\n'''''Dalej jest noc: losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski''''' (\"Night without End: The Fate of Jews in Selected Counties of Occupied Poland\"), co-edited by [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]] and [[Barbara Engelking]], is a two-volume study published in 2018 by the [[Polish Center for Holocaust Research]] in [[Warsaw, Poland]]. The 1,600-page study contains nine chapters, each covering a county in [[occupied Poland]] in 1939\u20131945\u2014[[Bielsk County|Bielsk Podlaski]], [[Bi\u0142goraj County|Bi\u0142goraj]], [[Bochnia County|Bochnia]], [[D\u0119bica County|D\u0119bica]], [[\u0141uk\u00f3w County|Luk\u00f3w]], [[Miech\u00f3w County|Miech\u00f3w]], [[Nowy Targ County|Nowy Targ]], [[W\u0119gr\u00f3w County|W\u0119gr\u00f3w]], and [[Z\u0142ocz\u00f3w]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski |url=https://www.academia.edu/37020664/Dalej_jest_noc._Losy_%C5%BByd%C3%B3w_w_wybranych_powiatach_okupowanej_Polski_Night_without_End_The_Fate_of_Jews_in_Selected_Counties_of_Occupied_Poland_2018_ |website=Academia.edu}}</ref>\u2014in the [[General Government]] area established by Germany in [[World War II]]. The study identifies small Polish towns as \"death traps\" for Jews in hiding.<ref name=\"JTA20180511\">[https://www.jta.org/2018/05/11/default/poles-helped-kill-jews-hiding-nazis-study-claims Study says Polish neighbors betrayed many more Jews than previously thought], [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], 11 May 2018.</ref> An abridged English-language version of the study is forthcoming.<ref name=\"Frydel\">[https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14623528.2018.1527091?journalCode=cjgr20 Frydel, Tomasz. \"The Ongoing Challenge of Producing an Integrated Microhistory of the Holocaust in East Central Europe.\" Journal of Genocide Research 20.4 (2018): 624\u2013631.]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nSeveral scholars, mainly associated with [[Poland]]'s [[Institute of National Remembrance]], have criticized ''Dalej jest noc'' for using unreliable sources, for ignoring the context of Germany's draconian occupation policies and practices, for some  authors' alleged personal interests, for selective treatment of witness statements (questioning Polish witnesses' statements, while taking at face value witness statements that were in line with authors' theses), and for presenting rumors and gossip as actual proven facts.<ref>Tomasz Doma\u0144ski,  [https://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/241621/Korektaobrazu.pdf ''\"Korekta obrazu? Refleksje \u017ar\u00f3d\u0142oznawcze wok\u00f3\u0142 ksi\u0105\u017cki ''Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski\" (\"A Corrected Picture?  Reflections on Use of Sources in the Book, ''Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski''\"], [[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]], ''[[Polish-Jewish Studies]]'', 2019, 72 pp.</ref><ref name=Roguski/><ref>[https://www.dzieje.pl/aktualnosci/ukazaly-sie-kolejne-trzy-recenzje-ipn-na-temat-publikacji-dalej-jest-noc] ''\"Ukaza\u0142y si\u0119 kolejne trzy recenzje IPN na temat publikacji'' [Three More [[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]] Reviews Have Appeared of] ''Dalej jest noc\"'', Dzieje.pl 21.02.19.</ref><ref>[[Dawid Golik]], ''\"Nowatorska noc. Kilka uwag na marginesie artyku\u0142u Karoliny Panz\"'' [\"Innovative Night:  Some Remarks about [[Karolina Panz]]'s Article\"], ''Zeszyty Historyczne WiN-u'' ''nr'' [no.] 47, 2018, pp. 109\u201334.</ref><ref>[[Jacek Borkowicz]], \"[https://www.rp.pl/Kraj/302109970-Wraca-spor-o-udzial-w-Zagladzie.html] ''\"Wraca sp\u00f3r o zag\u0142adzie\"'' [\"Argument over Genocide Returns\"], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 February 2019.</ref> \nHistorian [[Jacek Borkowicz]] writes in the Polish newspaper ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' that, using data from the book, he concludes that the actual number of Jewish victims of Poles was much lower, at most 40,000, while around 50,000 and possibly as many as 100,000 Jews were saved by Poles.<ref>[https://www.rp.pl/Plus-Minus/305179916-Pogruchotana-pamiec-o-Zagladzie.html] [[Jacek Borkowicz]], ''\"Pogruchotana pami\u0119\u0107 o Zag\u0142adzie\"'' [\"Mangled Memory of Genocide\"], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]: Plus Minus'', 17 May 2018.</ref> Tomasz Doma\u0144ski writes in ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' that the authors speak of a \"Polish-German administration\", whereas there was no Polish administration in German-occupied territories, and that the authors' use of materials is tendentiously selective. He also criticizes the misleading use of the expression \"Polish Police\" (the [[Blue Police]] was a German-run entity based on conscripted prewar Polish police officers) and the lack of a common definition of \"county\".<ref>[https://www.rp.pl/Kraj/302109970-Wraca-spor-o-udzial-w-Zagladzie.html] Wraca spor o udzial w Zagladzie</ref>\n\nHistorian [[Piotr Gontarczyk]] charges the book with \"scholarly mystification\". As an example of gross inaccuracy, Gontarczyk gives the book's description of events in the [[Bochnia Ghetto]] in German-occupied Poland. Gontarczyk writes that the book \"makes the [[Jewish Ghetto Police]] disappear, replacing it with Polish police.\"  The Bochnia Ghetto, he says, witnessed \"[[Inferno (Dante)|scenes out of Dante]], with the participation of the [[Jewish Ghetto Police]] (''J\u00fcdische Ordnungstdienst''); there were no ''Polish'' police [inside Jewish ghettos], but the book... says the bunkers [in which some Jews hid, hoping to escape deportation to German extermination camps] were searched by ''Polish'' police.\"<ref>[[Piotr Gontarczyk]],  ''[http://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/246298/GontarczykGlaukopis36.pdf \"Mi\u0119dzy nauk\u0105 a mistyfikacj\u0105, czyli o naturze pi\u015bmiennictwa prof. Jana Grabowskiego na podstawie casusu wsi Wrotn\u00f3w i Mi\u0119dzyle\u015b powiatu w\u0119growskiego\" (''\"Between Scholarship and Mystification:  On the Nature of Professor Jan Grabowski's Writings, Based on the Cases of the Villages of Wrotn\u00f3w and Mi\u0119dzyle\u015b in [[W\u0119gr\u00f3w County]]\"''), Glaukopis, ''no. 36, pp. 313\u2013323.'']</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.polskieradio.pl/321/1222/Artykul/2275685,Piotr-Gontarczyk-zarzuca-publikacji-Centrum-Badan-nad-Zaglada-Zydow-naukowa-mistyfikacje |title = Piotr Gontarczyk zarzuca publikacji Centrum Bada\u0144 nad Zag\u0142ad\u0105 \u017byd\u00f3w \"naukow\u0105 mistyfikacj\u0119\"  |publisher = polskieradio.pl |date = 10 March 2019 |access-date = 10 March 2019 |language= pl}}</ref> One of the book's authors, [[Dagmara Swa\u0142tek-Niewi\u0144ska]] has replied that Gontarczyk is incorrect, and that the book discusses the Jewish Ghetto Police in numerous places, and she in turn charges Gontarczyk with not having read the book thoroughly and with drawing incorrect conclusions from a cursory reading.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wyborcza.pl/alehistoria/7,121681,24574550,piotr-gontarczyk-i-tygodnik-sieci-zlapani-na-klamstwie-czyli.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Piotr Gontarczyk i tygodnik \"Sieci\" z\u0142apani na k\u0142amstwie, czyli nowa szko\u0142a polemiki o Zag\u0142adzie|last=Swa\u0142tek-Niewi\u0144ska|first=Dagmara|date=22 March 2019|website=wyborcza.pl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nHistorian {{ill|Jacek Chrobaczy\u0144ski|pl|Jacek Chrobaczy\u0144ski}} writes that the study is based on solid analysis of sources. He notes the naming of perpetrators and co-perpetrators \u2013 individuals who took over Jewish property \u2013 and participation by the Polish [[Blue Police]], [[Baudienst]], fire brigades, and military guards. He writes that the study is important in deconstructing some political myths and propaganda in Polish history writing, journalism,  church pronouncements, and politics. He concludes that the two volumes are \"solid and reliable scholarship\".<ref>[http://resgestae.up.krakow.pl/article/download/4604/4323 Chrobaczy\u0144ski, Jacek. \"Osaczeni, samotni, bezbronni... Refleksje po lekturze ksi\u0105\u017cki Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski (Polish with English abstract), T. I, II, pod redakcj\u0105 Barbary Engelking i Jana Grabowskiego, Warszawa 2018.\" Res Gestae 6 (2018): 266\u2013301.]</ref>\n\n[[Karolina Koprowska]], writes that the book focuses on micro-history studies and case-study analysis. She calls it a unique book with both a clear scholarly goal and a political message, taking a clear stance in the ongoing discussion in Poland about Polish-Jewish historical relations. She writes that the book is valuable for its solid methodology, rare and personal focus on micro-history, and demonstration of how significant were varying local characteristics, which resulted in widely different and not fully generalizable circumstances that Jews faced in different parts of occupied Poland. She does note that the book may, however, lack an overarching methodological conclusion and does not attempt a new grand theory of Polish-Jewish wartime history.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koprowska|first=Karolina|date=2018|title=Nocne i dzienne historie: do\u015bwiadczenie Zag\u0142ady na polskiej prowincji. (O ksi\u0105\u017cce \u201eDalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski\u201d)|url=https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=786184|journal=Wielog\u0142os|language=Polish|issue=36|pages=161\u2013174|issn=1897-1962}}</ref>\n\n[[Beth Holmgren]] writes that ''Dalej jest noc'' is a \"highly detailed, systematically organized, data-based analysis of how and by whom the [[Holocaust]] was perpetrated in nine separate Polish counties\".<ref>Holmgren, Beth. \"Holocaust History and Jewish Heritage Preservation: Scholars and Stewards Working in PiS-Ruled Poland.\" Shofar 37.1 (2019): 96\u2013107.</ref>\n\n[[Tomasz Roguski]]'s review of the book focuses particularly on the chapter by [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]]. Roguski writes that the book deals with an interesting topic that needs further research. He commends the authors for pioneering work but criticizes some of its methodology, its use of some primary sources to the neglect of others, its too narrow focus, and its statistical conclusions.<ref name=Roguski>Tomasz Roguski, ''[http://ipn.gov.pl/download/1/244267/RoguskiDalejjestnocGlaukopis36.pdf \"Dalej jest noc. Losy \u017byd\u00f3w w wybranych powiatach okupowanej Polski, red. Barbara Engelking i Jan Grabowski\", Glaukopis, ''no. 36, pp. 335\u2013356.'']</ref>\n\n==The missing [[Bielsko County]] chapter==\nPolish historian and [[religion|religions scholar]] [[Jacek Proszyk]] had been asked to work up [[Bielsko County]] for ''Dalej jest noc''.  However, he was unable to submit a finished text, largely because of methodological difficulties that he encountered. He \"[found it impossible to obtain] data sufficiently reliable to... perform statistical analysis and [to determine] the exact number of persons who perished, the exact number... who survived, and how they survived.\"  Proszyk concluded that he could only \"describe... verified individual cases.  The war\", he writes, \"was a great DESTRUCTION and LIE.  We do not have... complete archival records....  Even what we have is not always the truth.... [I]n Bielsko and Bia\u0142a [which were only part of the county that Proszyk was to have covered, in order to survive] Jews, Poles, and [anti-Nazi] Germans [all had to flee, lie, or pretend to be what they were not].  This falsehood left its [imprint] in the records and accounts, and that is why I [felt compelled] to verify... every account and every entry.\"  Proszyk was unable to submit generalized findings for Bielsko County, but he hopes to eventually prepare a study of particular individuals' experiences there. Proszyk's experience highlights the methodological difficulties in undertaking a reliable study of such subject matter.<ref>[[Jacek Proszyk]], ''\"Nienapisany rozdzia\u0142. Powiat bielski (Wschodni G\u00f3rny \u015al\u0105sk), niem. Landkreis Bielitz, Ost-Oberschlesien\"'' [\"Unwritten Chapter:  [[Bielsko County]] (Eastern [[Upper Silesia]]), [[German language|German]]:  ''Landkreis Bielitz, Ost-Oberschlesien''\"], ''Jacek Proszyk \u2013 w\u0142asne zapiski'' ([[Jacek Proszyk]]: Personal Notes), 21 May 2018.  [http://proszyk.blogspot.com/2018/05/nienapisany-rozdzia-powiat-bielski.html]</ref>\n\n==Litigation against editors==\n''Dalej jest noc'' accuses Edward Malinowski, ''so\u0142tys'' of the Polish village of Malinowo, of having been responsible for the deaths of dozens of Jews who, during World War II, were in hiding from the Germans. His 94-year-old relative Filomena Leszczy\u0144ska is suing Professors Engelking and Grabowski, the book's editors, in Warsaw court for defaming Malinowski, asserting that, on the contrary, he had assisted Jews, at the risk of his own life and the lives of his family.<ref>[https://www.tvp.info/42706332/pozew-przeciwko-engelking-i-grabowskiemu-zarzut-publikacja-zmyslonych-informacji] S\u0142awomir Cedzy\u0144ski, ''\"Pozew przeciwko Engelking i Grabowskiemu.  Zarzut:  publikacja zmy\u015blonych informacji\"'' (\"Court Summons for Engelking and Grabowski.  The Charge:  Publication of Fabricated Information\"), ''TVP INFO'', 20 May 2019.</ref><ref>[http://rdi.org.pl/] \"The RDI [Polish League against Defamation] Backs the Family of Edward Malinowski in Their Lawsuit against Prof. [[Barbara Engelking]] and Dr. [[Jan Grabowski (historian)|Jan Grabowski]]\", [[Polish League Against Defamation|Polish League against Defamation]], 21 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Hunt for the Jews]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:History books about the Holocaust]]\n[[Category:Books about Jewish Polish history]]\n[[Category:Polish-language books]]\n", "name_user": "Nihil novi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe missing Bielsko County chapter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalej_jest_noc"}
{"title_page": "Khalili Collections", "text_new": "{{short description|8 art collections of Nasser D. Khalili}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Khalili Collections\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo                = Khalili_Collections_logo.jpg\n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = Khalili Collections logo\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date and age|1970|df=yes}}<ref name=\"britishmuseum\" />\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| type                = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 35,000<ref name=\"britishmuseum\" />\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]]\n| executive_director  = \n| owner               = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{Official url}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Khalili Collections''' comprise eight distinct art collections assembled by [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]] over five decades.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/news/2019/renowned-collector-nasser-khalili-revealed-as-buyer-of-lost-monumental-meiji-vase-as-he-reunites-it-with-original-set/|title=Renowned collector Nasser Khalili revealed as buyer of 'lost' monumental Meiji vase as he reunites it with original set|first=Roland|last=Arkell|work=Antiques Trade Gazette|date=1 March 2019|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"britishmuseum\" /> Together, the collections include some 35,000 works of art,<ref name=\"britishmuseum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=221957|title=The Khalili Family Trust (Biographical details)|date=|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and each is considered among the most important in its field.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/the_khalili_collections_major_contributor_to_longing_for/|title=The Khalili Collections major contributor to \"Longing for Mecca\" exhibition at the Tropenmuseum in Amsterdam|last=|first=|date=16 April 2019|website=www.unesco.org|publisher=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmong these are the largest private collection of Islamic art, with 28,000 items including 2,000 ceramics and 600 items of jewellery. A separate collection includes around 4,000 objects relating to the [[Hajj]], spanning from the 7th century AD to the present day. From Japan, there are 1,600 items of [[Meiji (era)|Meiji era]] decorative art and another [[Khalili Collection of Kimono|collection of more than 450 Kimonos]], covering a 300 year period. The most comprehensive private collection of enamels, with over 1,300 items, includes items from China, Japan, Europe and Islamic lands. The eight collections also include 100 flatweave textiles from southern Sweden, 100 examples of Spanish [[Damascening|damascened]] metalwork (i.e. with metal inlaid into other metal), and 48 Aramaic documents from 4th century-BC [[Bactria]]. These various collections show two themes that commonly motivate private collections: collecting examples of the highest artistic merit and forming complete series.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Transcending boundaries: The arts of Islam: Treasures from the Nassar D. Khalili collection (Thesis)|last=Ryan|first=Louise|publisher=University of Western Sydney|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=82\u201387|id = {{ProQuest|1949737243}}}}</ref>\n\nOne hundred catalogues and monographs describing the collections are being published. There have been numerous public exhibitions drawn exclusively from the collections, as well as loans of items to heritage institutions.\n\n== Collections ==\n=== Islamic Art (700\u20132000) ===\nThe Khalili Collections include one of the world's most comprehensive collections of Islamic art<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204616504577172402386772604|title=The British Museum's Pilgrimage|last=McKie|first=Andrew|date=27 January 2012|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=10 September 2019|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-03-29/iranian-student-with-750-turns-billionaire-made-by-islamic-art|title=Iranian Student With $750 Turns Billionaire Made by Islamic Art|last=Green|first=William|date=30 March 2010|work=Bloomberg|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and the largest in private hands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/healing-the-world-with-art-560103.html|title=Healing the world with art|last=Gayford|first=Martin|date=16 April 2004|work=The Independent|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f526cb06-98f5-11e1-9da3-00144feabdc0|title=A leap of faith|last=Moore|first=Susan|date=12 May 2012|work=Financial Times|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/arts/2010/12/101214_khalili_collection.shtml|title=BBC World Service - Arts & Culture - Khalili Collection: Picture gallery|last=|first=|date=14 December 2010|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Islamic Art includes 28,000 objects documenting arts from Islamic lands over a period of almost 1400 years. It was described in 1998 as \"one of the largest and most representative collections of [[Quran]]ic manuscripts in the world\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Irwin|first=Robert|date=November 1998|title=Review: Calligraphic Significances: Catalogues of the Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Islamic Art|journal=British Journal of Middle Eastern Studies|publisher=Taylor & Francis|volume=25|issue=2|pages=355\u2013361|jstor=40662688}}</ref> and is the largest private collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-abbasid-tradition-qurans-of-the-8th-to-the-10th-centuries-ad/|title=The Abbasid Tradition: Qur'ans of the 8th to the 10th centuries AD|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Abbasid Tradition Qur'ans of the 8th And 10th Centuries Ad.|date=2005|publisher=I B Tauris & Co Ltd|others=Deroche, Francois.|isbn=9781874780519|oclc=954219022}}</ref> Khalili is motivated by a belief that Islamic art is the most beautiful, yet has been underappreciated by the wider world.<ref name=\":4\" /> The collection has been described as presenting art works of interest to Westerners without abstracting them away from the aesthetic standards of Islamic culture.<ref name=\":4\" /> Khalili defines Islamic art as \"art produced by Muslim artists for Muslim patrons\", and only a minority of the items have an explicitly religious purpose.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn addition to rare and illustrated manuscripts, the collection includes album and miniature paintings,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/paintings-from-india/|title=Paintings from India|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> lacquer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/lacquer-of-the-islamic-lands-part-one/|title=Lacquer of the Islamic Lands (Part One and Part Two)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> ceramics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/cobalt-and-lustre-the-first-centuries-of-islamic-pottery/|title=Cobalt and Lustre: The first centuries of Islamic pottery|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> glass and rock crystal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/glass-from-sasanian-antecedents-to-european-imitations/|title=Glass: From Sasanian antecedents to European imitations|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> metalwork,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/brasses-bronze-and-silver-of-the-islamic-lands-part-one/|title=Brasses, Bronze & Silver of the Islamic Lands|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> arms and armour,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-arts-of-war-arms-and-armour-of-the-7th-to-19th-centuries/|title=The Arts of War: Arms and Armour of the 7th to 19th centuries|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> jewellery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/gems-and-jewels-of-mughal-india-jewelled-and-enamelled-objects-from-the-16th-to-20th-centuries/|title=Gems and Jewels of Mughal India. Jewelled and enamelled objects from the 16th to 20th centuries|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> carpets and textiles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/textiles-carpets-and-costumes-part-one/|title=Textiles, Carpets and Costumes|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> over 15,000 coins<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/dinars-dirhams-coins-islamic-lands-later-period-part-one/|title=Dinars and Dirhams. Coins of the Islamic lands. The early period (Part One)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and architectural elements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/monuments-and-memorials-carvings-and-tile-work-from-the-islamic-world/|title=Monuments and Memorials. Carvings and tile work from the Islamic world|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> The ceramic collection, numbering around 2,000 items, has been described as particularly strong in pottery of the [[Timurid Empire|Timurid era]] and also pottery of pre-Mongol [[Bamyan|Bamiyan]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baker|first=Phil|date=December 1995|title=Khalili's collection|journal=The Art Book|language=en|volume=2|issue=4|pages=8|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8357.1995.tb00290.x|issn=1368-6267}}</ref> The jewellery collection includes more than 600 rings, many purely decorative but some with religious inscriptions or having a secular function, such as [[Seal (emblem)|signet rings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/ornament-and-amulet-rings-of-the-islamic-lands/|title=Ornament and Amulet: Rings of the Islamic Lands|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Around two hundred objects relate to [[Science in the medieval Islamic world|medieval Islamic science and medicine]], including astronomical instruments for orienting towards Mecca, scales and weights, and supposedly magical items intended for medical use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/science-tools-magic-part-one-body-and-spirit-mapping-the-universe/|title=Science, Tools & Magic: (Part One) Body and Spirit, Mapping the Universe; (Part Two) Mundane Worlds|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis collection was the basis in 2008 for the first comprehensive exhibition of Islamic art to be staged in the Middle East, at the Emirates Palace in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\":2\" /> This was also the largest exhibition of Islamic art held anywhere up to that date.<ref name=\":2\" /> Exhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] in Sydney, the [[Arab World Institute|Institut du Monde Arabe]] in Paris and the [[Nieuwe Kerk, Amsterdam|Nieuwe Kerk]] in Amsterdam as well as at many other museums and institutions worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHighlights include pages from some of the most famous manuscripts with [[Persian miniature]]s, including the [[Great Mongol Shahnameh]] (c. 1330s), 10 folios from the [[Shahnameh of Shah Tahmasp]] (c. 1520),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-tale-and-the-image-history-and-epic-paintings-from-iran-and-turkey-part-one/|title=History and epic paintings from Iran and Turkey (Part One)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and 59 folios from the oldest manuscript of the [[Jami' al-tawarikh|Jami al-tawarikh]] (1314), [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid-al-Din]]\u2019s world history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-the-jami-al-tawarikh-of-rashid-al-din-mss727-folio-54a/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} The Jami' al-Tawarikh of Rashid al-Din|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> There is also a 13th-century saddle from the era of [[Genghis Khan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-saddle-fittings-and-horse-trappings-mtw795/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} Saddle Fittings and Horse Trappings|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and an [[astrolabe]] commissioned by [[Shah Jahan]] (1648\u201358).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-large-planispheric-astrolabe-sci53/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} A monumental planispheric astrolabe...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' has said that it is the greatest collection of Islamic Art in existence.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to Edward Gibbs, Chairman of Middle East and India at [[Sotheby's|Sotheby's]], it is the best such collection in private hands.<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 06.jpg|Saddle Fittings and Horse Trappings, Central Asia or western frontiers of China, circa 1200\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 01.jpg|Single Folio from a Qur\u2019an, probably Mecca or Madinah, early 8th century AD\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 03.jpg|Folio from the [[Shahnameh of Shah Tahmasp]], [[Tabriz]], 1520s\u20131540s \nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 04.jpg|Noah's Ark, from The [[Jami\u2018 al-Tawarikh]] of [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]], Tabriz, 1314\u201315\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 05.jpg|A monumental planispheric [[astrolabe]] made for Shah Jahan, Punjab, Lahore, 1648\u201358 \nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 02.jpg|Carpet with Star Medallions, Ushak, western Anatolia, Turkey, late 15th or early 16th century\n</gallery>\n\n=== Hajj and the Arts of Pilgrimage (700\u20132000) ===\nAlongside the [[Topkap\u0131 Palace|Topkap\u0131 Palace museum]], the collection is considered the largest and most significant group of objects relating to the cultural history of the [[Hajj]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Makkah: a Celebration of Unity|last=Scotland|first=Patricia|publisher=FIRST|year=2017|isbn=9780995728141|location=London|pages=|chapter=Foreword|author-link=Patricia Scotland|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kibofoundation.org/collections/category/40|title=Khalili Collections {{!}} Hajj and The Arts of Pilgrimage|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kibofoundation.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> It holds objects and archival documents from all over the Islamic world, from the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad period]] to the 21st century.<ref name=\":8\" /> It includes over 300 textiles and many other objects such as coins, medals, miniatures, manuscripts and photographs relating to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\":8\" /> In total, the collection contains approximately 4,000 objects.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nHighlights include a [[Litter (vehicle)|mahmal]] (AH 1067 (AD 1656\u20137)) commissioned by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] Sultan [[Mehmed IV|Mehmet IV]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage/khalili-collection-hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage-a-complete-cover-for-a-damascus-mahmal-txt289/|title=Hajj and The Arts of Pilgrimage {{!}} A Complete Cover...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> coverings for the door of the [[Kaaba]],<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/themes/hajj/the_sacred_textiles_of_mecca.aspx|title=The sacred textiles of Mecca|last=|first=|date=|website=Hajj|publisher=British Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> curtains for the mosque of the Prophet in Medina, covering for the [[Maqam Ibrahim|Station of Abraham]],<ref name=\":9\" /> the earliest known accurate eyewitness account of Mecca<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage/khalili-collection-islamic-art-panoramic-view-of-mecca-mss1077/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} Panoramic View of Mecca|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and some of the earliest photographs taken of Mecca and the Hajj, by photography pioneer Mohammed Sadiq Bey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://islamicart.museumwnf.org/database_item.php?id=object;EPM;uk;Mus22;2;en|title=Photographic views of Hajj, by Muhammad Sadiq Bey|last=Khan|first=Qaisra|date=|website=Discover Islamic Art|publisher=Museum With No Frontiers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Mahmal cover.jpg|A Complete Cover for a Damascus Mahmal, Istanbul, 16th century\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Kabah curtain.jpg|Curtain for Door of the Kaaba, Cairo, 1015 AH (1606 AD)\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Mecca panorama.jpg|Panoramic View of Mecca, 1845\n</gallery>\n\n=== Aramaic Documents (535BC-324BC) ===\n[[File:Khalili Collection Aramaic Documents manuscript Bactria.jpg|thumb|A Long List of Supplies Disbursed, [[Bactria]], starts on 15 [[Sivan]], year 7 of [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]], corresponding to 8 June 324BC]]\nThe collection comprises 48 historically significant [[Aramaic]] documents from [[Bactria|Ancient Bactria]], consisting of mainly letters and accounts related to the court of the [[satrap]] of Bactria. Together these letters and accounts make up the oldest known correspondence of the administration of [[Bactria]] and [[Sogdia]]na.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Aramaic documents from ancient Bactria (fourth century BCE.) from the Khalili collections|publisher=|others=Naveh, Joseph,, Shaked, Shaul,, Khalili, Nasser D.,, Khalili Family Trust|year=2012|isbn=978-1874780748|location=London|pages=x|oclc=818222949}}</ref> The documents, written in Official Aramaic, were likely to originate from the historical city of [[Balkh]] and all are dated within a period of less than 30 years, between 353&nbsp;BC to 324&nbsp;BC.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Aramaic documents from ancient Bactria (fourth century BCE.) from the Khalili collections|publisher=|others=Naveh, Joseph,, Shaked, Shaul,, Khalili, Nasser D.,, Khalili Family Trust|year=2012|isbn=978-1874780748|location=London|pages=18|oclc=818222949}}</ref> The newest of the documents was written during [[Alexander the Great]]\u2019s early reign in the region, using the name \u2018Alexandros\u2019 (\u2018Iksndrs\u2019) by which he later became known.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/aramaic-documents/khalili-collection-aramaic-documents-a-long-list-of-supplies-disbursed-ia17/|title=Aramaic Documents {{!}} A Long List of Supplies...|last=|first=|date=2016|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Japanese Art of the Meiji Period (1868\u20131912) ===\n{{main|Khalili Collection of Japanese Art}}\nThe collection of Meiji decorative arts is only comparable in terms of quality to the collection of the [[Imperial House of Japan|Japanese Imperial family]].<ref name=\":5\" /> It comprises over 1,600 pieces, including metalwork, enamels, lacquer, textiles and ceramics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period/|title=Japanese Art of the Meiji Period|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> The [[Meiji (era)|Meiji]] period saw a cultural revolution in Japan where traditional tastes were met with international ones. Since the beginning of [[Emperor Meiji]]\u2019s reign in Japan, European and international collectors have sought pieces of Japanese art from this era. Many works in the collections were produced by Imperial Court artists and were exhibited at the [[Great Exhibition]]s of the late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Splendors of Meiji : treasures of imperial Japan : masterpieces from the Khalili Collection|last=Earle|first=Joe|publisher=Broughton International Inc|year=1999|isbn=1874780137|location=St. Petersburg, Fla.|pages=10|oclc=42476594}}</ref>\n\nHighlights include works by imperial court artists [[Shibata Zeshin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/shibata-zeshin-masterpieces-of-japanese-lacquer-from-the-khalili-collection/|title=Shibata Zeshin, Masterpieces of Japanese lacquer from the Khalili Collection|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> [[Namikawa Yasuyuki]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-enamel/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Enamel|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> [[Makuzu K\u014dzan|Makuzu Kozan]],<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/treasures-of-imperial-japan-ceramics-from-the-khalili-collection/|title=Treasures of Imperial Japan, Ceramics from the Khalili Collection|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Yabu Meizan,<ref name=\":6\" /> Kano Natsuo,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-metalwork-part-one/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Metalwork Parts One & Two|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Suzuki Chokichi,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period/khalili-collections-japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period-incense-burner-and-cover-m62/|title=Japanese Art of the Meiji Period {{!}} Incense Burner...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and Shirayama Shosai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-lacquer-part-one/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Lacquer Part One|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nExhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the [[British Museum]], [[Israel Museum]], [[Van Gogh Museum]], [[Portland Museum of Art|Portland Museum]], [[Moscow Kremlin Museums]], and at many other museums and institutions worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" />\n<gallery>\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_incense_burner.jpg|Incense Burner (Koro), Japan, 1890\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_pair_of_samurai.jpg|Pair of Samurai Figures, Japan, 1890\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_waves_panel.jpg|\u2018Waves\u2019 Panel, Japan, 1888-1890\n</gallery>\n\n=== Japanese [[Kimono]] (1700\u20132000) ===\n\n{{main|Khalili Collection of Kimono}}\n\nThe collection represents three hundred years of the Japanese textile industry and contains over 450 garments. The garments have been worn to demonstrate gender, age, status and wealth throughout Japan's history. The core of the collection is made up of kimono from the [[Edo period|Edo]] (1603\u20131868), [[Meiji (era)|Meiji]] (1868\u20131912), [[Taish\u014d|Taisho]] (1912\u20131926) and early [[Sh\u014dwa (1926\u20131989)|Showa]] (1926\u20131989) eras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/kimono/|title=Khalili Collecitons {{!}} Kimono|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kimono : the art and evolution of Japanese fashion : the Khalili collections|others=Jackson, Anna,, Nagasaki, Iwao,, Screech, Timon,, Guth, Christine,, Brown, Kendall H.,, \u9577\u5d0e\u5dcc|isbn=9780500518021|location=London|oclc=917375803|last1 = Jackson|first1 = Anna|year = 2015}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 02.jpg|Kimono for a Young Woman ([[Furisode]]), Japan, 1912-1926\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 01.jpg|Outer Kimono for a Woman (Uchikake), Japan, 1920-1930\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 03.jpg|Outer Kimono for a Young Woman (Uchikake), Japan, 1840-1870\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 04.jpg|Kimono for a Girl (Furisode), Japan, 1920-1940\n</gallery>\n\n=== Swedish Textiles (1700\u20131900) ===\n[[File:Khalili Collection Swedish Textiles Carriage Cushion Cover.jpg|thumb|Carriage Cushion Cover (Two Lions in Floral Roundels), Sweden, Scania, Bara district, late 18th century]]\nThe collection consists mostly of textile panels, cushion and bed covers from the [[Scania]] region of southern Sweden, dating in the main from a hundred-year-old period of the mid-18th to mid-19th centuries. The majority of the pieces in the collection were made for wedding ceremonies in the region. While they played a part in the ceremonies, they were also a reflection of the artistry and skill of the weaver. Their designs often consist of symbolic illustrations of fertility and long life. The entire collection is made up of 100 pieces.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008 it was described as \"the only extensive collection of Swedish flatweaves outside the country\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e3450b58-f171-11dc-a91a-0000779fd2ac|title=The collection is a symphony|last=Moore|first=Susan|date=17 March 2008|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nExhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the Swedish Cultural Institute in Paris and Boston University Art Gallery.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Spanish Damascene Metalwork (1850\u20131900) ===\nOne of the largest collections of its kind, the Spanish Metalwork collection pays homage to the [[Ignacio Zuloaga|Zuloaga]] family, which played a major part in the preservation of [[damascening]] in Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/ornament-and-malta/|title=Metal Magic: Spanish Treasures from the Khalili Collection, The Auberge de Provence, Valetta, Malta|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The collection contains pieces created by [[Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga]] between 1834\u20131910. Some of the pieces, such as a giant iron [[cassone]], were originally acquired by the 19th-century English collector, [[Alfred Morrison]].<ref name=\"Spanish Damascene Metalwork\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/spanish-damascene-metalwork/|title=Spanish Damascene Metalwork|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The entire collection comprises over 100 pieces,<ref>[[Alan Borg|Borg, Alan]], \"Preface\", in {{Cite book|title=The art and tradition of the Zuloagas : Spanish damascene from the Khalili Collection|last=Lavin|first=James D.|date=1997|publisher=Khalili Family Trust in association with the Victoria and Albert Museum|others=Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro., Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Spanish Metalwork., Victoria and Albert Museum., Museo de Bellas Artes de Bilbao.|isbn=1874780102|location=[London?]|pages=|oclc=37560664}}</ref> 22 of which are signed by Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga.<ref name=\"Spanish Damascene Metalwork\"/>\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascene Metalwork cassone, Elbar.jpg|thumb|Iron Cassone, Spain, [[Eibar]], 1871]]\nAt the opening of the Khalili Zuloago exhibition at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London, its then director [[Alan Borg]] said it was \"a landmark in the study of 19th century Spanish decorative art\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/media/comments-and-reviews/|title=Comments & Reviews|last=|first=|date=December 2009|website=nasserdkhalili.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> Other exhibitions also drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the [[Bilbao Fine Arts Museum]] and [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]] in Granada.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Enamels of the World (1700\u20132000) ===\nThe collection consists of over 1300 pieces and showcases the global significance and evolution of [[Vitreous enamel|enamelling]], covering a 300-year period.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/enamels-of-the-world/|title=Enamels Of The World|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> It is the most comprehensive private collection of its kind.<ref name=\":10\" /> The uniqueness of the collection lies in its geographic, artistic and historical range, including pieces from China, Japan, Islamic countries and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/enamels-of-the-world-1700-2000/|title=Enamels of the World \u2013 1700\u20132000|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> Highlights include the enamelled chariot belonging to the Indian Maharaja of [[Bhavnagar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/enamels-of-the-world/khalili-collection-enamels-of-the-world-landau-carriage-ind1008/|title=Enamels of the World {{!}} Landau Carriage|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and a painted enamel throne table with the seal mark of the 18th century Chinese [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong emperor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/enamels-of-the-world/khalili-collections-enamels-of-the-world-throne-table-ch648/|title=Enamels of the World {{!}} Throne Table|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Other objects include presentation chargers, jewellery, miniatures and ornamental pieces.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nAt the 2009\u201310 ''Enamels of the world'' exhibition held at the [[Hermitage Museum|State Hermitage Museum]], its director [[Mikhail Piotrovsky]] said \"unique in its scope, the Collection reveals the remarkable technical achievements of the enamellers and encourages a greater awareness of the range of their activity.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n<gallery>\nKhalili_Collection_Enamels_of_the_World_Chariot_of_Maharaja_of_Bhavnagar.jpg|Enamelled chariot belonging to the Indian Maharaja of [[Bhavnagar]]\nKhalili_Collection_Enamels_of_the_World_throne_table.jpg|Painted enamel throne table with the seal mark of the [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong emperor]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Publications ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Publications Selection.jpg|thumb|A selection of the over 100 publications representing the eight collections]]\nThe Khalili Collections are represented in 70 publications, including exhibition catalogues, with work in progress to extend this to 100. The total costs associated with the conservation, research, scholarship and publication of the collections are estimated to be in the tens of millions of [[Pound Sterling|pounds]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art-market-mysterious-gifts-from-the-east-who-is-the-man-who-has-collected-islams-finest-treasures-1563284.html|title=Art Market: Mysterious gifts from the East|last=Norman|first=Geraldine|date=13 December 1992|work=The Independent|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Islamic Art (700\u20132000) ===\n*{{cite book|author1=D\u00e9roche|first=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Volume I \u2013 The Abbasid Tradition: Qur'ans of the 8th to the 10th centuries AD|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780519|location=|pages=|author-link=Fran\u00e7ois D\u00e9roche}}\n*{{cite book|author1=James|first=David|title=Volume II \u2013 The Master Scribes: Qur'ans of the 10th to 14th centuries AD|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780526|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=James|first=David|title=Volume III \u2013 After Timur: Qur'ans of the 15th and 16th centuries|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276020|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|last2=Contadini|first2=Anna|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume IV, Part I \u2013 The Decorated Word: Qur'ans of the 17th to 19th centuries|url=|year=1999|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276037|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|last2=Contadini|first2=Anna|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume IV, Part II \u2013 The Decorated Word: Qur'ans of the 17th to 19th centuries|url=|year=2009|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780540|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Safwat|first=Nabil F.|title=Volume V \u2013 The Art of the Pen: Calligraphy of the 14th to 20th Centuries|url=|year=1996|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276044|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Khan|first=Geoffrey|title=Volume VI \u2013 Bills, Letters and Deeds: Arabic Papyri of the 7th to 11th Centuries|url=|year=1993|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780564|location=|pages=|author-link=Geoffrey Khan}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Freeman|first=Deborah|title=Volume VII \u2013 Learning, Piety and Poetry. Manuscripts from the Islamic world|url=|year=1993|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780847|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Leach|first=Linda York|title=Volume VIII \u2013 Paintings from India|url=|year=1998|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276242|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Grube|first=Ernst J.|title=Volume IX \u2013 Cobalt and Lustre: The first centuries of Islamic pottery|url=|year=1994|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276075|location=|pages=|author-link=Ernst J. Grube}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Grube|first=Ernst J.|title=Volume X \u2013 A Rival to China. Later Islamic pottery|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780878|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Spink|first=Michael|title=Volume XI \u2013 Brasses, Bronze & Silver of the Islamic Lands, Part I and II|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780885|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Maddison|first=Francis|title=Volume XII \u2013 Science, Tools & Magic: Body and Spirit, Mapping the Universe, Part I and Mundane Bodies, Part II|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276105|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|title=Volume XIII \u2013 Seals and Talismans|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780779|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Cohen|first=Steven|title=Volume XIV \u2013 Textiles, Carpets and Costumes, Part I and II|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780786|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Goldstein|first=Sidney M.|title=Volume XV \u2013 Glass: From Sasanian antecedents to European imitations|url=|year=2005|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780502|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Wenzel|first=Marian|title=Volume XVI \u2013 Ornament and Amulet: Rings of the Islamic Lands|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276143|location=|pages=|author-link=Marian Wenzel}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Spink|first=Michael|last2=Ogden|first2=Jack|title=Volume XVII \u2013 The Art of Adornment: Jewellery of the Islamic lands|url=|year=2013|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780861|location=|pages=|author-link2=Jack Ogden (jewellery historian)}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Carvalho|first=Pedro Moura|title=Volume XVIII \u2013 Gems and Jewels of Mughal India. Jewelled and enamelled objects from the 16th to 20th centuries|url=|year=2010|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780724|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Darley-Doran|first=Robert|last2=Darley-Doran|first2=Elisabeth|last3=Bates|first3=Michael L.|title=Volume XIX \u2013 Dinars and Dirhams. Coins of the Islamic lands. The early period, Part I|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780823|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Darley-Doran|first=Robert|last2=Darley-Doran|first2=Elisabeth|last3=Bates|first3=Michael L.|title=Volume XX \u2013 Dinars and Dirhams. Coins of the Islamic lands. The later period, Part II|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780830|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Alexander|first=David|title=Volume XXI \u2013 The Arts of War: Arms and Armour of the 7th to 19th centuries|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780618|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Khalili|first=Nasser D.|last2=Robinson|first2=B. W.|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume XXII \u2013 Lacquer of the Islamic Lands, Part I|url=|year=1996|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780625|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Khalili|first=Nasser D.|last2=Robinson|first2=B. W.|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume XXII \u2013 Lacquer of the Islamic Lands, Part II|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780632|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Vernoit|first=Stephen|title=Volume XXIII \u2013 Occidentalism. Islamic Art in the 19th Century|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276204|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Pinder-Wilson|first=Ralph|last2=Crites|first2=Mitchell Abdul Karim|last3=Abraham|first3=Rudolf|title=Volume XXIV \u2013 Monuments and Memorials. Carvings and tile work from the Islamic world|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780854|location=|pages=|author-link=Ralph Pinder-Wilson}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Sims|first=Eleanor|last2=Bayani|first2=Manijeh|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume XXV, Part I \u2013 The Tale and the Image. Illustrated manuscripts and album paintings from Iran and Turkey (Part One)|url=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780809|location=|pages=|date=28 February 2006}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Rogers|first=J. M.|last2=Bayani|first2=Manijeh|title=Volume XXV, Part II \u2013 The Tale and the Image. Illustrated manuscripts and album paintings from Iran and Turkey (Part Two)|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780816|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Blair|first=Shelia|title=Volume XXVII \u2013 A Compendium of Chronicles: Rashid al-Din's illustrated history of the world|url=|year=1995|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780656|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Studies in The Khalili Collection \u2013 Academic Monographs ===\n*{{cite book|author1=Khan|first=Geoffrey|title=Volume I \u2013 Selected Arabic Papyri|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780663|location=|pages=|author-link=Geoffrey Khan}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Soucek|first=Svat|title=Volume II \u2013 Piri Reis and Turkish Mapmaking after Columbus, The Khalili Portolan Atlas|url=|year=1996|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780670|location=|pages=|author-link=Svat Soucek}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Sims-Williams|first=Nicholas|title=Volume III \u2013 (Part One) Bactrian Documents from Northern Afghanistan, Legal and Economic Documents|url=|year=2012|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780922|location=|pages=|author-link=Nicholas Sims-Williams}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Sims-Williams|first=Nicholas|title=Volume III \u2013 (Part Two) Bactrian Documents from Northern Afghanistan, Letters and Buddhist Texts|url=|year=2007|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780908|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Sims-Williams|first=Nicholas|title=Volume III \u2013 (Part Three) Bactrian Documents from Northern Afghanistan, Plates|url=|year=2012|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780915|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Goodwin|first=Tony|title=Volume IV \u2013 Arab-Byzantine Coinage|url=|year=2005|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780755|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Khan|first=Geoffrey|title=Volume V \u2013 Arabic Documents from Early Islamic Khurasan|url=|year=2007|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780717|location=|pages=|author-link=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Chaldecott|first=Nada|title=Volume VI \u2013 Turcoman Jewellery|url=|year=2020|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780939|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Aramaic Documents (400 BC \u2013 AD 700) ===\n*{{cite book|author1=Naveh|first=Joseph|last2=Shaked|first2=Shaul|title=Aramaic Documents from Ancient Bactria|url=|year=2012|publisher=Khalili Family Trust|isbn=9781874780748|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Japanese Art of the Meiji Period (1868\u20131912) ===\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|title=Volume I \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Selected Essays|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780014}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|title=Volume II \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Metalwork Parts One & Two|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780021}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|title=Volume III \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Enamel|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780038}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|first3=Joe|last3=Earle|title=Volume IV \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Lacquer Parts One & Two|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780045}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|title=Volume V, Part I \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Ceramics Part One: Porcelain|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780052}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Oliver|last1=Impey|first2=Malcolm|last2=Fairley|title=Volume V, Part II \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Ceramics Part Two: Earthenware|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780069}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Earle|first=Joe|title=Volume VI \u2013 MEIJI NO TAKARA \u2013 Treasures of Imperial Japan; Masterpieces by Shibata Zeshin|url=|year=1995|publisher=Kibo Foundation|isbn=9781874780083|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Japanese Kimono ===\n*{{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Anna|title=Kimono: The Japanese Art of Pattern and Fashion|url=|date=2015|publisher=Thames & Hudson|isbn=9780500518021|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Swedish textile art ===\n*{{cite book|author1=Hansen|first=Viveka|author2=Institutet f\u00f6r Kulturforskning|title=Swedish Textile Art: Traditional Marriage Weavings from Scania: The Khalili Collection|url=|date=1996|publisher=Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780076|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Spanish Damascene metalwork ===\n*{{cite book|author1=Lavin|first=James D.|last2=Larra\u00f1aga|first2=Ramiro|title=The Art and Tradition of the Zuloagas: Spanish Damascene from the Khalili Collection|url=|year=1997|publisher=Khalili Family Trust|isbn=9781874780113|location=|pages=}}\n\n=== Enamels ===\n*{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Haydn|title=Enamels of the World, 1700-2000: The Khalili Collections|url=|year=2009|publisher=Khalili Family Trust|isbn=9781874780175|location=|pages=}}\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nThe following exhibitions were drawn exclusively from the Khalili Collections.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/the-eight-collections-2/|title=The Eight Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=nasserdkhalili.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Islamic art ===\n''Empire of the Sultans: Ottoman Art from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* July \u2013 Sep 1995 Musee Rath, Geneva, Switzerland\n* July \u2013 Oct 1996 Brunei Gallery, School of Oriental and African Studies, London, UK\n* Dec 1996 \u2013 June 1997 Israel Museum, Jerusalem, Israel\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2000 Society of the Four Arts, Palm Beach, Florida, USA\n\n''Marvels of the East: Indian Paintings of the Mughal Period from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* May \u2013 July 2000,Tel Aviv Museum of Art, Israel\n\n''Empire of the Sultans: Ottoman Art from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* July \u2013 Oct 2000 Detroit Institute of Arts, Detroit, Michigan, USA\n* Oct 2000 \u2013 Jan 2001 Albuquerque Museum of Art & History, Albuquerque, New Mexico, USA\n* Jan \u2013 Apr 2001 Portland Art Museum, Portland, Oregon, USA\n* Aug \u2013 Oct 2001 Asian Art Museum of San Francisco, San Francisco, California, USA\n* Oct 2001 \u2013 Jan 2002 Bruce Museum of Arts and Science, Greenwich, Connecticut, USA\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2002 Milwaukee Art Museum, Milwaukee, Wisconsin, USA\n* May \u2013 July 2002 North Carolina Museum of Art, Raleigh, North Carolina, USA\n* Aug 2002 \u2013 Jan 2003 Museum of Art, Brigham Young University, Provo, Utah, USA\n\n''Ornements de la Perse: Islamic Patterns in 19th Century Europe''\n\n* Oct \u2013 Dec 2002 Leighton House Museum, London, UK\n\n''Empire of the Sultans: Ottoman Art from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2003 Oklaho