 der Sammlung Khalili''\n\n* Feb \u2013 June 2007 Kunsthalle Krems, Krems, Austria\n\n''Beyond Imagination: Treasures of Imperial Japan from The Khalili Collection, 19th to early 20th century''\n\n* July \u2013 October 2017 Moscow Kremlin Museums, Moscow, Russia\n\n=== Spanish Damascene Metalwork ===\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Spanish Treasures from The Khalili Collection''\n\n* May 1997 \u2013 Jan 1998 Victoria and Albert Museum, London, UK\n\n''El Arte y Tradici\u00f3n de los Zuloaga: Damasquinado Espa\u00f1ol de la Colecci\u00f3n Khalili''\n\n* May \u2013 Aug 2000 Museo de Bellas Artes, Bilbao, Spain\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2001 Alhambra Palace, Granada, Spain\n* May \u2013 Sep 2001 Real Fundacion de Toledo, Toledo, Spain\n\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Meisterwerke in gold, silber und eisen damaszener\u2013schmiedekunst aus der Khalili-Sammlung''\n\n* Apr \u2013 Aug 2003 Roemer und Pelizaeus Museum, Hildesheim, Germany\n\n''Metal Magic: Spanish Treasures from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Nov 2011 \u2013 Apr 2012 Auberge de Provence, Valletta, Malta\n\n=== Swedish Textiles ===\n''Swedish Textile Art: The Khalili Collection''\n\n* Feb \u2013 Mar 1996 IK Foundation, Pildammarnas Vattentorn, Malmo, Sweden\n\n''Textiles de Scanie des XVIII et XIX Si\u00e8cles dans la Collection Khalili''\n\n* Mar \u2013 May 2000 Swedish Cultural Centre, Paris, France\n\n''A Monument to Love: Swedish Marriage Textiles from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Sep \u2013 Oct 2003 Boston University Art Gallery, Boston, Massachusetts, USA\n\n=== Enamels of  the World ===\n''Enamels of the World 1700\u20132000 from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Dec 2009 \u2013 Apr 2010 State Hermitage Museum, St Petersburg, Russia\n\n== Loans to museums and galleries ==\nThe collections have also loaned items for display in many countries.<ref name=\":0\" />  ''Earthly Beauty, Heavenly Art: The Art of Islam'', an exhibition of objects from the Islamic collection and the State Hermitage Museum was seen at\n*[[Nieuwe Kerk (Amsterdam)|Nieuwe Kerk]], Amsterdam, Dec 1999 \u2013 Apr 2000 \n*State Hermitage Museum, St Petersburg, 2000 \u2013 Sep 2001      \n*Hermitage Rooms, [[Somerset House]], London (as ''Heaven on Earth: Art From Islamic Lands \u2013 Selected objects from the Khalili Collection and The State Hermitage Museum'', March \u2013 August 2004\n\n== References ==\n{{Free-content attribution\n|title=  The Khalili Collections\n|author = Khalili Foundation\n|source=  <!-- The source of the work if not from the publisher or the author -->\n|documentURL= https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/the-eight-collections-2/\n|license statement URL= <!-- The URL of the license statement of the work if not included within the document -->\n|license= CC-BY-SA 4.0\n|howto= <!-- Only necessary if the template is used multiple times on the same page. Any value here will hide the last two sentences about instructions. -->\n}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://artsandculture.google.com/partner/the-khalili-collections Khalili Collections on Google Arts & Culture]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6HC5hmABcAQ Sky Arts documentary about the collections]\n\n[[Category:Private art collections]]\n[[Category:Art collections in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Islamic art]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Aramaic texts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|8 art collections of Nasser D. Khalili}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Khalili Collections\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo                = Khalili_Collections_logo.jpg\n| logo_upright        = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = Khalili Collections logo\n| former_name         = \n| established         = {{Start date and age|1970|df=yes}}<ref name=\"britishmuseum\" />\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| type                = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = 35,000<ref name=\"britishmuseum\" />\n| visitors            = \n| founder             = [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]]\n| executive_director  = \n| owner               = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{Official url}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Khalili Collections''' comprise eight distinct art collections assembled by [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]] over five decades.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/news/2019/renowned-collector-nasser-khalili-revealed-as-buyer-of-lost-monumental-meiji-vase-as-he-reunites-it-with-original-set/|title=Renowned collector Nasser Khalili revealed as buyer of 'lost' monumental Meiji vase as he reunites it with original set|first=Roland|last=Arkell|work=Antiques Trade Gazette|date=1 March 2019|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"britishmuseum\" /> Together, the collections include some 35,000 works of art,<ref name=\"britishmuseum\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=221957|title=The Khalili Family Trust (Biographical details)|date=|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and each is considered among the most important in its field.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/the_khalili_collections_major_contributor_to_longing_for/|title=The Khalili Collections major contributor to \"Longing for Mecca\" exhibition at the Tropenmuseum in Amsterdam|last=|first=|date=16 April 2019|website=www.unesco.org|publisher=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmong these are the largest private collection of Islamic art, with 28,000 items including 2,000 ceramics and 600 items of jewellery. A separate collection includes around 4,000 objects relating to the [[Hajj]], spanning from the 7th century AD to the present day. From Japan, there are 1,600 items of [[Meiji (era)|Meiji era]] decorative art and another [[Khalili Collection of Kimono|collection of more than 450 Kimonos]], covering a 300 year period. The most comprehensive private collection of enamels, with over 1,300 items, includes items from China, Japan, Europe and Islamic lands. The eight collections also include 100 flatweave textiles from southern Sweden, 100 examples of Spanish [[Damascening|damascened]] metalwork (i.e. with metal inlaid into other metal), and 48 Aramaic documents from 4th century-BC [[Bactria]]. These various collections show two themes that commonly motivate private collections: collecting examples of the highest artistic merit and forming complete series.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Transcending boundaries: The arts of Islam: Treasures from the Nassar D. Khalili collection (Thesis)|last=Ryan|first=Louise|publisher=University of Western Sydney|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=82\u201387|id = {{ProQuest|1949737243}}}}</ref>\n\nOne hundred catalogues and monographs describing the collections are being published. There have been numerous public exhibitions drawn exclusively from the collections, as well as loans of items to heritage institutions.\n\n== Collections ==\n=== Islamic Art (700\u20132000) ===\nThe Khalili Collections include one of the world's most comprehensive collections of Islamic art<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204616504577172402386772604|title=The British Museum's Pilgrimage|last=McKie|first=Andrew|date=27 January 2012|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=10 September 2019|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-03-29/iranian-student-with-750-turns-billionaire-made-by-islamic-art|title=Iranian Student With $750 Turns Billionaire Made by Islamic Art|last=Green|first=William|date=30 March 2010|work=Bloomberg|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> and the largest in private hands.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/healing-the-world-with-art-560103.html|title=Healing the world with art|last=Gayford|first=Martin|date=16 April 2004|work=The Independent|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f526cb06-98f5-11e1-9da3-00144feabdc0|title=A leap of faith|last=Moore|first=Susan|date=12 May 2012|work=Financial Times|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/arts/2010/12/101214_khalili_collection.shtml|title=BBC World Service - Arts & Culture - Khalili Collection: Picture gallery|last=|first=|date=14 December 2010|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Islamic Art includes 28,000 objects documenting arts from Islamic lands over a period of almost 1400 years. It was described in 1998 as \"one of the largest and most representative collections of [[Quran]]ic manuscripts in the world\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Irwin|first=Robert|date=November 1998|title=Review: Calligraphic Significances: Catalogues of the Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Islamic Art|journal=British Journal of Middle Eastern Studies|publisher=Taylor & Francis|volume=25|issue=2|pages=355\u2013361|jstor=40662688}}</ref> and is the largest private collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-abbasid-tradition-qurans-of-the-8th-to-the-10th-centuries-ad/|title=The Abbasid Tradition: Qur'ans of the 8th to the 10th centuries AD|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Abbasid Tradition Qur'ans of the 8th And 10th Centuries Ad.|date=2005|publisher=I B Tauris & Co Ltd|others=Deroche, Francois.|isbn=9781874780519|oclc=954219022}}</ref> Khalili is motivated by a belief that Islamic art is the most beautiful, yet has been underappreciated by the wider world.<ref name=\":4\" /> The collection has been described as presenting art works of interest to Westerners without abstracting them away from the aesthetic standards of Islamic culture.<ref name=\":4\" /> Khalili defines Islamic art as \"art produced by Muslim artists for Muslim patrons\", and only a minority of the items have an explicitly religious purpose.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn addition to rare and illustrated manuscripts, the collection includes album and miniature paintings,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/paintings-from-india/|title=Paintings from India|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> lacquer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/lacquer-of-the-islamic-lands-part-one/|title=Lacquer of the Islamic Lands (Part One and Part Two)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> ceramics,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/cobalt-and-lustre-the-first-centuries-of-islamic-pottery/|title=Cobalt and Lustre: The first centuries of Islamic pottery|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> glass and rock crystal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/glass-from-sasanian-antecedents-to-european-imitations/|title=Glass: From Sasanian antecedents to European imitations|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> metalwork,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/brasses-bronze-and-silver-of-the-islamic-lands-part-one/|title=Brasses, Bronze & Silver of the Islamic Lands|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> arms and armour,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-arts-of-war-arms-and-armour-of-the-7th-to-19th-centuries/|title=The Arts of War: Arms and Armour of the 7th to 19th centuries|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> jewellery,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/gems-and-jewels-of-mughal-india-jewelled-and-enamelled-objects-from-the-16th-to-20th-centuries/|title=Gems and Jewels of Mughal India. Jewelled and enamelled objects from the 16th to 20th centuries|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> carpets and textiles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/textiles-carpets-and-costumes-part-one/|title=Textiles, Carpets and Costumes|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> over 15,000 coins<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/dinars-dirhams-coins-islamic-lands-later-period-part-one/|title=Dinars and Dirhams. Coins of the Islamic lands. The early period (Part One)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and architectural elements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/monuments-and-memorials-carvings-and-tile-work-from-the-islamic-world/|title=Monuments and Memorials. Carvings and tile work from the Islamic world|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> The ceramic collection, numbering around 2,000 items, has been described as particularly strong in pottery of the [[Timurid Empire|Timurid era]] and also pottery of pre-Mongol [[Bamyan|Bamiyan]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baker|first=Phil|date=December 1995|title=Khalili's collection|journal=The Art Book|language=en|volume=2|issue=4|pages=8|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8357.1995.tb00290.x|issn=1368-6267}}</ref> The jewellery collection includes more than 600 rings, many purely decorative but some with religious inscriptions or having a secular function, such as [[Seal (emblem)|signet rings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/ornament-and-amulet-rings-of-the-islamic-lands/|title=Ornament and Amulet: Rings of the Islamic Lands|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Around two hundred objects relate to [[Science in the medieval Islamic world|medieval Islamic science and medicine]], including astronomical instruments for orienting towards Mecca, scales and weights, and supposedly magical items intended for medical use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/science-tools-magic-part-one-body-and-spirit-mapping-the-universe/|title=Science, Tools & Magic: (Part One) Body and Spirit, Mapping the Universe; (Part Two) Mundane Worlds|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis collection was the basis in 2008 for the first comprehensive exhibition of Islamic art to be staged in the Middle East, at the Emirates Palace in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name=\":2\" /> This was also the largest exhibition of Islamic art held anywhere up to that date.<ref name=\":2\" /> Exhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] in Sydney, the [[Arab World Institute|Institut du Monde Arabe]] in Paris and the [[Nieuwe Kerk, Amsterdam|Nieuwe Kerk]] in Amsterdam as well as at many other museums and institutions worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHighlights include pages from some of the most famous manuscripts with [[Persian miniature]]s, including the [[Great Mongol Shahnameh]] (c. 1330s), 10 folios from the [[Shahnameh of Shah Tahmasp]] (c. 1520),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/the-tale-and-the-image-history-and-epic-paintings-from-iran-and-turkey-part-one/|title=History and epic paintings from Iran and Turkey (Part One)|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and 59 folios from the oldest manuscript of the [[Jami' al-tawarikh|Jami al-tawarikh]] (1314), [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid-al-Din]]\u2019s world history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-the-jami-al-tawarikh-of-rashid-al-din-mss727-folio-54a/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} The Jami' al-Tawarikh of Rashid al-Din|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> There is also a 13th-century saddle from the era of [[Genghis Khan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-saddle-fittings-and-horse-trappings-mtw795/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} Saddle Fittings and Horse Trappings|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> and an [[astrolabe]] commissioned by [[Shah Jahan]] (1648\u201358).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/islamic-art/khalili-collection-islamic-art-large-planispheric-astrolabe-sci53/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} A monumental planispheric astrolabe...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' has said that it is the greatest collection of Islamic Art in existence.<ref name=\":1\" /> According to Edward Gibbs, Chairman of Middle East and India at [[Sotheby's|Sotheby's]], it is the best such collection in private hands.<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 06.jpg|Saddle Fittings and Horse Trappings, Central Asia or western frontiers of China, circa 1200\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 01.jpg|Single Folio from a Qur\u2019an, probably Mecca or Madinah, early 8th century AD\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 03.jpg|Folio from the [[Shahnameh of Shah Tahmasp]], [[Tabriz]], 1520s\u20131540s \nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 04.jpg|Noah's Ark, from The [[Jami\u2018 al-Tawarikh]] of [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]], Tabriz, 1314\u201315\nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 05.jpg|A monumental planispheric [[astrolabe]] made for Shah Jahan, Punjab, Lahore, 1648\u201358 \nFile:Khalili Collection Islamic Art 02.jpg|Carpet with Star Medallions, Ushak, western Anatolia, Turkey, late 15th or early 16th century\n</gallery>\n\n=== Hajj and the Arts of Pilgrimage (700\u20132000) ===\nAlongside the [[Topkap\u0131 Palace|Topkap\u0131 Palace museum]], the collection is considered the largest and most significant group of objects relating to the cultural history of the [[Hajj]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Holy Makkah: a Celebration of Unity|last=Scotland|first=Patricia|publisher=FIRST|year=2017|isbn=9780995728141|location=London|pages=|chapter=Foreword|author-link=Patricia Scotland|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kibofoundation.org/collections/category/40|title=Khalili Collections {{!}} Hajj and The Arts of Pilgrimage|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kibofoundation.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> It holds objects and archival documents from all over the Islamic world, from the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad period]] to the 21st century.<ref name=\":8\" /> It includes over 300 textiles and many other objects such as coins, medals, miniatures, manuscripts and photographs relating to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]].<ref name=\":8\" /> In total, the collection contains approximately 4,000 objects.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nHighlights include a [[Litter (vehicle)|mahmal]] (AH 1067 (AD 1656\u20137)) commissioned by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] Sultan [[Mehmed IV|Mehmet IV]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage/khalili-collection-hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage-a-complete-cover-for-a-damascus-mahmal-txt289/|title=Hajj and The Arts of Pilgrimage {{!}} A Complete Cover...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> coverings for the door of the [[Kaaba]],<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/themes/hajj/the_sacred_textiles_of_mecca.aspx|title=The sacred textiles of Mecca|last=|first=|date=|website=Hajj|publisher=British Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> curtains for the mosque of the Prophet in Medina, covering for the [[Maqam Ibrahim|Station of Abraham]],<ref name=\":9\" /> the earliest known accurate eyewitness account of Mecca<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/hajj-and-the-arts-of-pilgrimage/khalili-collection-islamic-art-panoramic-view-of-mecca-mss1077/|title=Islamic Art {{!}} Panoramic View of Mecca|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and some of the earliest photographs taken of Mecca and the Hajj, by photography pioneer Mohammed Sadiq Bey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://islamicart.museumwnf.org/database_item.php?id=object;EPM;uk;Mus22;2;en|title=Photographic views of Hajj, by Muhammad Sadiq Bey|last=Khan|first=Qaisra|date=|website=Discover Islamic Art|publisher=Museum With No Frontiers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Mahmal cover.jpg|A Complete Cover for a Damascus Mahmal, Istanbul, 16th century\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Kabah curtain.jpg|Curtain for Door of the Kaaba, Cairo, 1015 AH (1606 AD)\nFile:Khalili Collection Hajj Mecca panorama.jpg|Panoramic View of Mecca, 1845\n</gallery>\n\n=== Aramaic Documents (535BC-324BC) ===\n[[File:Khalili Collection Aramaic Documents manuscript Bactria.jpg|thumb|A Long List of Supplies Disbursed, [[Bactria]], starts on 15 [[Sivan]], year 7 of [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]], corresponding to 8 June 324BC]]\nThe collection comprises 48 historically significant [[Aramaic]] documents from [[Bactria|Ancient Bactria]], consisting of mainly letters and accounts related to the court of the [[satrap]] of Bactria. Together these letters and accounts make up the oldest known correspondence of the administration of [[Bactria]] and [[Sogdia]]na.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Aramaic documents from ancient Bactria (fourth century BCE.) from the Khalili collections|publisher=|others=Naveh, Joseph,, Shaked, Shaul,, Khalili, Nasser D.,, Khalili Family Trust|year=2012|isbn=978-1874780748|location=London|pages=x|oclc=818222949}}</ref> The documents, written in Official Aramaic, were likely to originate from the historical city of [[Balkh]] and all are dated within a period of less than 30 years, between 353&nbsp;BC to 324&nbsp;BC.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Aramaic documents from ancient Bactria (fourth century BCE.) from the Khalili collections|publisher=|others=Naveh, Joseph,, Shaked, Shaul,, Khalili, Nasser D.,, Khalili Family Trust|year=2012|isbn=978-1874780748|location=London|pages=18|oclc=818222949}}</ref> The newest of the documents was written during [[Alexander the Great]]\u2019s early reign in the region, using the name \u2018Alexandros\u2019 (\u2018Iksndrs\u2019) by which he later became known.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/aramaic-documents/khalili-collection-aramaic-documents-a-long-list-of-supplies-disbursed-ia17/|title=Aramaic Documents {{!}} A Long List of Supplies...|last=|first=|date=2016|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Japanese Art of the Meiji Period (1868\u20131912) ===\nThe collection of Meiji decorative arts is only comparable in terms of quality to the collection of the [[Imperial House of Japan|Japanese Imperial family]].<ref name=\":5\" /> It comprises over 1,600 pieces, including metalwork, enamels, lacquer, textiles and ceramics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period/|title=Japanese Art of the Meiji Period|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> The [[Meiji (era)|Meiji]] period saw a cultural revolution in Japan where traditional tastes were met with international ones. Since the beginning of [[Emperor Meiji]]\u2019s reign in Japan, European and international collectors have sought pieces of Japanese art from this era. Many works in the collections were produced by Imperial Court artists and were exhibited at the [[Great Exhibition]]s of the late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Splendors of Meiji : treasures of imperial Japan : masterpieces from the Khalili Collection|last=Earle|first=Joe|publisher=Broughton International Inc|year=1999|isbn=1874780137|location=St. Petersburg, Fla.|pages=10|oclc=42476594}}</ref>\n\nHighlights include works by imperial court artists [[Shibata Zeshin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/shibata-zeshin-masterpieces-of-japanese-lacquer-from-the-khalili-collection/|title=Shibata Zeshin, Masterpieces of Japanese lacquer from the Khalili Collection|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> [[Namikawa Yasuyuki]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-enamel/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Enamel|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> [[Makuzu K\u014dzan|Makuzu Kozan]],<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/treasures-of-imperial-japan-ceramics-from-the-khalili-collection/|title=Treasures of Imperial Japan, Ceramics from the Khalili Collection|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Yabu Meizan,<ref name=\":6\" /> Kano Natsuo,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-metalwork-part-one/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Metalwork Parts One & Two|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Suzuki Chokichi,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period/khalili-collections-japanese-art-of-the-meiji-period-incense-burner-and-cover-m62/|title=Japanese Art of the Meiji Period {{!}} Incense Burner...|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and Shirayama Shosai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/meiji-no-takara-treasures-of-imperial-japan-lacquer-part-one/|title=MEIJI NO TAKARA - Treasures of Imperial Japan; Lacquer Part One|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nExhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the [[British Museum]], [[Israel Museum]], [[Van Gogh Museum]], [[Portland Museum of Art|Portland Museum]], [[Moscow Kremlin Museums]], and at many other museums and institutions worldwide.<ref name=\":0\" />\n<gallery>\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_incense_burner.jpg|Incense Burner (Koro), Japan, 1890\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_pair_of_samurai.jpg|Pair of Samurai Figures, Japan, 1890\nKhalili_Collection_Japanese_Meijji_waves_panel.jpg|\u2018Waves\u2019 Panel, Japan, 1888-1890\n</gallery>\n\n=== Japanese [[Kimono]] (1700\u20132000) ===\n\n{{main|Khalili Collection of Kimono}}\n\nThe collection represents three hundred years of the Japanese textile industry and contains over 450 garments. The garments have been worn to demonstrate gender, age, status and wealth throughout Japan's history. The core of the collection is made up of kimono from the [[Edo period|Edo]] (1603\u20131868), [[Meiji (era)|Meiji]] (1868\u20131912), [[Taish\u014d|Taisho]] (1912\u20131926) and early [[Sh\u014dwa (1926\u20131989)|Showa]] (1926\u20131989) eras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/kimono/|title=Khalili Collecitons {{!}} Kimono|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kimono : the art and evolution of Japanese fashion : the Khalili collections|others=Jackson, Anna,, Nagasaki, Iwao,, Screech, Timon,, Guth, Christine,, Brown, Kendall H.,, \u9577\u5d0e\u5dcc|isbn=9780500518021|location=London|oclc=917375803|last1 = Jackson|first1 = Anna|year = 2015}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 02.jpg|Kimono for a Young Woman ([[Furisode]]), Japan, 1912-1926\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 01.jpg|Outer Kimono for a Woman (Uchikake), Japan, 1920-1930\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 03.jpg|Outer Kimono for a Young Woman (Uchikake), Japan, 1840-1870\nFile:Khalili Collection Kimono 04.jpg|Kimono for a Girl (Furisode), Japan, 1920-1940\n</gallery>\n\n=== Swedish Textiles (1700\u20131900) ===\n[[File:Khalili Collection Swedish Textiles Carriage Cushion Cover.jpg|thumb|Carriage Cushion Cover (Two Lions in Floral Roundels), Sweden, Scania, Bara district, late 18th century]]\nThe collection consists mostly of textile panels, cushion and bed covers from the [[Scania]] region of southern Sweden, dating in the main from a hundred-year-old period of the mid-18th to mid-19th centuries. The majority of the pieces in the collection were made for wedding ceremonies in the region. While they played a part in the ceremonies, they were also a reflection of the artistry and skill of the weaver. Their designs often consist of symbolic illustrations of fertility and long life. The entire collection is made up of 100 pieces.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008 it was described as \"the only extensive collection of Swedish flatweaves outside the country\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e3450b58-f171-11dc-a91a-0000779fd2ac|title=The collection is a symphony|last=Moore|first=Susan|date=17 March 2008|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nExhibitions drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the Swedish Cultural Institute in Paris and Boston University Art Gallery.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Spanish Damascene Metalwork (1850\u20131900) ===\nOne of the largest collections of its kind, the Spanish Metalwork collection pays homage to the [[Ignacio Zuloaga|Zuloaga]] family, which played a major part in the preservation of [[damascening]] in Spain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/ornament-and-malta/|title=Metal Magic: Spanish Treasures from the Khalili Collection, The Auberge de Provence, Valetta, Malta|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The collection contains pieces created by [[Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga]] between 1834\u20131910. Some of the pieces, such as a giant iron [[cassone]], were originally acquired by the 19th-century English collector, [[Alfred Morrison]].<ref name=\"Spanish Damascene Metalwork\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/spanish-damascene-metalwork/|title=Spanish Damascene Metalwork|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> The entire collection comprises over 100 pieces,<ref>[[Alan Borg|Borg, Alan]], \"Preface\", in {{Cite book|title=The art and tradition of the Zuloagas : Spanish damascene from the Khalili Collection|last=Lavin|first=James D.|date=1997|publisher=Khalili Family Trust in association with the Victoria and Albert Museum|others=Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro., Nasser D. Khalili Collection of Spanish Metalwork., Victoria and Albert Museum., Museo de Bellas Artes de Bilbao.|isbn=1874780102|location=[London?]|pages=|oclc=37560664}}</ref> 22 of which are signed by Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga.<ref name=\"Spanish Damascene Metalwork\"/>\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascene Metalwork cassone, Elbar.jpg|thumb|Iron Cassone, Spain, [[Eibar]], 1871]]\nAt the opening of the Khalili Zuloago exhibition at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London, its then director [[Alan Borg]] said it was \"a landmark in the study of 19th century Spanish decorative art\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/media/comments-and-reviews/|title=Comments & Reviews|last=|first=|date=December 2009|website=nasserdkhalili.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> Other exhibitions also drawing exclusively from the collection have been held at the [[Bilbao Fine Arts Museum]] and [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]] in Granada.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Enamels of the World (1700\u20132000) ===\nThe collection consists of over 1300 pieces and showcases the global significance and evolution of [[Vitreous enamel|enamelling]], covering a 300-year period.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/enamels-of-the-world/|title=Enamels Of The World|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> It is the most comprehensive private collection of its kind.<ref name=\":10\" /> The uniqueness of the collection lies in its geographic, artistic and historical range, including pieces from China, Japan, Islamic countries and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/portfolio/enamels-of-the-world-1700-2000/|title=Enamels of the World \u2013 1700\u20132000|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref> Highlights include the enamelled chariot belonging to the Indian Maharaja of [[Bhavnagar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/enamels-of-the-world/khalili-collection-enamels-of-the-world-landau-carriage-ind1008/|title=Enamels of the World {{!}} Landau Carriage|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> and a painted enamel throne table with the seal mark of the 18th century Chinese [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong emperor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/collections/enamels-of-the-world/khalili-collections-enamels-of-the-world-throne-table-ch648/|title=Enamels of the World {{!}} Throne Table|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> Other objects include presentation chargers, jewellery, miniatures and ornamental pieces.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nAt the 2009\u201310 ''Enamels of the world'' exhibition held at the [[Hermitage Museum|State Hermitage Museum]], its director [[Mikhail Piotrovsky]] said \"unique in its scope, the Collection reveals the remarkable technical achievements of the enamellers and encourages a greater awareness of the range of their activity.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n<gallery>\nKhalili_Collection_Enamels_of_the_World_Chariot_of_Maharaja_of_Bhavnagar.jpg|Enamelled chariot belonging to the Indian Maharaja of [[Bhavnagar]]\nKhalili_Collection_Enamels_of_the_World_throne_table.jpg|Painted enamel throne table with the seal mark of the [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong emperor]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Publications ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Publications Selection.jpg|thumb|A selection of the over 100 publications representing the eight collections]]\nThe Khalili Collections are represented in 70 publications, including exhibition catalogues, with work in progress to extend this to 100. The total costs associated with the conservation, research, scholarship and publication of the collections are estimated to be in the tens of millions of [[Pound Sterling|pounds]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art-market-mysterious-gifts-from-the-east-who-is-the-man-who-has-collected-islams-finest-treasures-1563284.html|title=Art Market: Mysterious gifts from the East|last=Norman|first=Geraldine|date=13 December 1992|work=The Independent|access-date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Islamic Art (700\u20132000) ===\n*{{cite book|author1=D\u00e9roche|first=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Volume I \u2013 The Abbasid Tradition: Qur'ans of the 8th to the 10th centuries AD|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780519|location=|pages=|author-link=Fran\u00e7ois D\u00e9roche}}\n*{{cite book|author1=James|first=David|title=Volume II \u2013 The Master Scribes: Qur'ans of the 10th to 14th centuries AD|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780526|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=James|first=David|title=Volume III \u2013 After Timur: Qur'ans of the 15th and 16th centuries|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276020|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|last2=Contadini|first2=Anna|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume IV, Part I \u2013 The Decorated Word: Qur'ans of the 17th to 19th centuries|url=|year=1999|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276037|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|last2=Contadini|first2=Anna|last3=Stanley|first3=Tim|title=Volume IV, Part II \u2013 The Decorated Word: Qur'ans of the 17th to 19th centuries|url=|year=2009|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780540|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Safwat|first=Nabil F.|title=Volume V \u2013 The Art of the Pen: Calligraphy of the 14th to 20th Centuries|url=|year=1996|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276044|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Khan|first=Geoffrey|title=Volume VI \u2013 Bills, Letters and Deeds: Arabic Papyri of the 7th to 11th Centuries|url=|year=1993|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780564|location=|pages=|author-link=Geoffrey Khan}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Freeman|first=Deborah|title=Volume VII \u2013 Learning, Piety and Poetry. Manuscripts from the Islamic world|url=|year=1993|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780847|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Leach|first=Linda York|title=Volume VIII \u2013 Paintings from India|url=|year=1998|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276242|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Grube|first=Ernst J.|title=Volume IX \u2013 Cobalt and Lustre: The first centuries of Islamic pottery|url=|year=1994|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276075|location=|pages=|author-link=Ernst J. Grube}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Grube|first=Ernst J.|title=Volume X \u2013 A Rival to China. Later Islamic pottery|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780878|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Spink|first=Michael|title=Volume XI \u2013 Brasses, Bronze & Silver of the Islamic Lands, Part I and II|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780885|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Maddison|first=Francis|title=Volume XII \u2013 Science, Tools & Magic: Body and Spirit, Mapping the Universe, Part I and Mundane Bodies, Part II|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276105|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Bayani|first=Manijeh|title=Volume XIII \u2013 Seals and Talismans|url=|year=1997|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780779|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Cohen|first=Steven|title=Volume XIV \u2013 Textiles, Carpets and Costumes, Part I and II|url=|year=|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780786|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Goldstein|first=Sidney M.|title=Volume XV \u2013 Glass: From Sasanian antecedents to European imitations|url=|year=2005|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780502|location=|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Wenzel|first=Marian|title=Volume XVI \u2013 Ornament and Amulet: Rings of the Islamic Lands|url=|year=1992|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9780197276143|location=|pages=|author-link=Marian Wenzel}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Spink|first=Michael|last2=Ogden|first2=Jack|title=Volume XVII \u2013 The Art of Adornment: Jewellery of the Islamic lands|url=|year=2013|publisher=The Nour Foundation|isbn=9781874780861|location=|pages=|author-link2=Jack Ogden (jewellery historian)}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Carvalho|first=Pedro Moura|title=Volume XVIII \u2013 Gems and Jewels of Mughal India. Jewelled and enamelled objects from the 